<rss version="2.0" xmlns:atom="http://www.w3.org/2005/Atom"><channel><title><![CDATA[The Atlantic - MOST-POPULAR]]></title><link/> https://www.theatlantic.com/most-popular/<atom:link href="https://rsshub.app/theatlantic/most-popular" rel="self" type="application/rss+xml"></atom:link><description><![CDATA[The Atlantic - MOST-POPULAR - Made with love by RSSHub(https://github.com/DIYgod/RSSHub)]]></description><generator> RS集线器</generator><webmaster>i@diygod.me (DIYgod)</webmaster><language> zh-cn</language><lastbuilddate> 2023 年 8 月 9 日星期三 02:00:22 GMT</lastbuilddate><ttl> 120 </ttl><item><title><![CDATA[The Abortion Backlash Reaches Ohio]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>民主党在该州罕见的胜利显示了自<em>罗伊</em>倒台以来共和党权力的局限性。 <br><figure><img src="https://cdn.theatlantic.com/thumbor/96KKsinuui57JYTWUFvpabh1PZU=/0x0:3600x2025/960x540/media/img/mt/2023/08/h_16069426/original.jpg" alt="照片显示俄亥俄州提前投票站外的“投赞成票”和“投反对票”标志" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><figcaption>麦迪·麦加维 / 纽约时报 / Redux</figcaption></figure>从官方角度来看，堕胎与俄亥俄州选民今天拒绝的宪法修正案无关。这个词没有出现在选票上，堕胎法也不会因为结果而改变。<br><br>然而，从实践和政治角度来看，被称为“问题一”的投票倡议的失败全部与堕胎有关，这为生殖权利倡导者提供了自最高法院推翻<i>罗伊诉韦德案</i>以来今年一系列胜利中的最新胜利。由于担心 11 月堕胎权修正案获得通过，俄亥俄州的共和党人要求选民批准一项提案，该提案将提高州宪法修改的门槛，目前该法案需要简单多数票。 <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/politics/archive/2023/08/ohio-issue-1-special-election-abortion/674923/">今天投票的措施</a>将把门槛提高到 60%。<br><br>参加夏季特别选举的俄亥俄州选民人数异常多，但选民人数有所下降。他们的决定是民主党在共和党占主导地位的州取得的罕见胜利，这表明堕胎仍然是选民进入明年总统选举的强大动力。俄亥俄州的结果可能会刺激堕胎权倡导者加大力度，通过将问题直接摆在选民面前来规避共和党控制的州立法机构。他们有理由对自己的机会感到乐观：自从最高法院对<i>多布斯诉杰克逊妇女健康组织案</i>做出裁决以来，全州范围内的堕胎权投票措施一直没有被击败，在佛蒙特州和加利福尼亚州等蓝州以及诸如此类的红州获胜。如堪萨斯州和肯塔基州。<br><br> <a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/politics/archive/2023/08/ohio-issue-1-special-election-abortion/674923/">阅读：下一场堕胎大战</a><br><br>去年夏天，在堪萨斯州，堕胎权一方以<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/politics/archive/2022/08/kansas-abortion-vote/671029/">18 个百分点的优势获胜，</a>令这个社会保守州的两党成员感到震惊。然而，到了俄亥俄州投票的最后一天，第一个问题的失败已不再令人意外。几周来，已经习惯了俄亥俄州失望的民主党人看到该州大城市和郊区县的提前投票人数飙升。如果共和党人希望通过将选举安排在八月的三伏天来吸引选民的注意，那么他们就打错了算盘。当我最近在该州旅行时，我在远离大城市的地区的前院和教堂外看到了<span class="smallcaps">“不投票”的</span>标志，进步的组织者告诉我，志愿者正在报名参加夏季竞选活动，其程度是闻所未闻的。反对派还包括一些独立选民和共和党选民，他们认为该提案剥夺了他们的权利。 “正是在这个‘别踩我’的时刻，选民被激活了，”俄亥俄州共同事业组织的执行董事凯瑟琳·特瑟说，该组织是一个善政倡导组织，帮助领导了击败修正案的努力。<br><br>第一个问题的反对者组建了一个两党联盟，其中包括两名前共和党州长。他们的信息重点广泛，呼吁选民“保护多数统治”并阻止立法机关公然夺权。但这次特别选举与今年秋天俄亥俄州堕胎公投的明显联系促使人们参加投票，特别是女性和年轻选民。 “选民不会花很多时间思考俄亥俄州宪法。他们可能不会花大量时间考虑投票权，”特瑟告诉我。但是，她说，“试图稀释选民的权力，从而影响对生殖权利的投票，这使得它变得非常具体，这很重要。”<br><br>去年，南达科他州和阿肯色州的选民拒绝了类似的共和党推动的让投票倡议更难通过的努力。但俄亥俄州作为一个大的前摇摆州的地位在过去十年里已经变成了红色，这对迫切希望在该州复兴本党的民主党人来说是一次独特的考验。 “我们在俄亥俄州被击败了很多次，”丹尼斯·威拉德（Dennis Willard）告诉我，他是该州的一名长期党员，也是反对派竞选活动的首席发言人。他说，共和党人试图通过这项修正案，“证明他们相信自己是不可战胜的，我们无法击败他们。”<br><br>第一个问题的失败可能为选民今年秋天保证俄亥俄州堕胎的机会扫清了道路，并且它将为进步人士开辟一条途径，以简单多数票将其他政策写入州宪法，包括大麻合法化和堕胎合法化。更高的最低工资——他们无法通过共和党控制的立法机构。包括威拉德在内的民主党人正在寻求一项修正案，以遏制曾帮助共和党锁定多数席位的不公正选区。他们还希望今晚的胜利能让俄亥俄州重新回到政治版图上。威拉德说：“我们的胜利向全国其他地区传达了一个信息，即俄亥俄州拥有可能性。” “十一月的胜利向人们表明，你不能再忽视俄亥俄州了。”<br><br><a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/politics/archive/2022/08/kansas-abortion-vote/671029/">阅读：堪萨斯州堕胎震惊事件</a><br><br>不过，目前共和党几乎没有失去对国家控制权的危险。它控制着立法机关两院的绝对多数席位；去年，共和党州长迈克·德温 (Mike DeWine) 以 25 个百分点的优势击败了民主党对手，赢得了第二个任期。一位俄亥俄州共和党人在今天的选举前匿名发言，他告诉我，第一个问题的失败和预期在 11 月通过的生殖权利修正案实际上可能会在明年对该党有所帮助，因为选民可能不再相信堕胎面临危险。在该州。 （共和党去年在纽约和加利福尼亚等蓝州表现更好，这些州的堕胎权并未受到严重威胁。）<br><br>俄亥俄州和其他类似投票措施失败的州的共和党人现在面临着他们权力的限制和选民反抗的时刻。他们会受到惩罚并重新调整，还是会继续突破界限？在确认他们失败的选票被清点之前，第一个问题的支持者不想考虑这个问题。然而，他们的批评者怀疑共和党人是否会改变他们的策略。 “他们不太可能立即停止，”特瑟说。 “要经历多次失败，他们才会明白选民不想被利用。”<br><br></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Wed, 09 Aug 2023 01:01:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.theatlantic.com/politics/archive/2023/08/ohio-special-election-issue-1-abortion/674957/</guid><link/> https://www.theatlantic.com/politics/archive/2023/08/ohio-special-election-issue-1-abortion/674957/ </item><item><title><![CDATA[How to Make a Four-Day Workweek Sustainable]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>减少工作时间可能会非常好，也可能非常糟糕。执行很重要。 <br><figure><img src="https://cdn.theatlantic.com/thumbor/BEi8kvliU3Gzfdqrkl-VNdFB2dk=/8x512:4723x3164/960x540/media/img/mt/2023/08/GettyImages_92982287/original.jpg" alt="三部电梯" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><figcaption>快闪流行/盖蒂</figcaption></figure><small><i>这是</i>《大西洋<i>日报》的一个版本，是一份时事通讯，可引导您了解当天最大的故事，帮助您发现新想法，并推荐最好的文化。</i> <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/newsletters/sign-up/atlantic-daily/"><i>在这里注册。</i></a></small><br><br>理论上，每周工作四天听起来不错。但如何才能真正使这种做法可持续发展呢？<br><br>首先，这是<i>《大西洋月刊》</i>的四个新故事：<br><br><li> <a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/culture/archive/2023/08/jason-aldean-country-music-luke-combs/674952/">当小镇的骄傲听起来像愤怒时</a></li><li><a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/magazine/archive/2023/09/jarell-jackson-shahjahan-mccaskill-killed-philadelphia-social-media/674760/">社交媒体是否让美国的谋杀案激增变得更糟？</a></li><li><a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2023/08/uk-trans-rights-labour-party/674944/">英国的性别战争已经结束。</a></li><li> <a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2023/08/trees-xenia-street-washington-dc-local-government/674949/">树？不在我的后院。</a></li><strong>更少的时间，相同的工作量？</strong><br><br>每周工作四天的想法听起来很诱人：在较短的时间内高效工作，然后享受三天周末的好处。在此过程中，员工可以<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/family/archive/2021/06/four-day-workweek/619222/">在个人生​​活中找到平衡并蓬勃发展</a>。一些雇主也热衷于此，因为他们寻求改善员工的健康和保留率。但执行很重要。最好的情况：缩短工作周<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.npr.org/2019/11/04/776163853/microsoft-japan-says-4-day-workweek-boosted-workers-productivity-by-40">可以提高生产力</a>并减少倦怠。最坏的情况是：已经在争先恐后地完成所有工作的工人面临着不可持续的压力，要求更快地完成工作。<br><br>近年来，世界各地的公司和政府一直在考虑在维持工资的同时减少工作时间的想法，特别是在标准每周工作 40 小时的白领行业（当然，这些行业中的许多人<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://news.gallup.com/poll/175286/hour-workweek-actually-longer-seven-hours.aspx">最终的工作时间超过了这个数字）</a> ）。一家名为 4 Day Week Global 的非营利倡导组织与学者进行试验并提倡缩短工作周，该组织<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.4dayweek.com/long-term-2023-pilot-results">发布了</a>与自愿参与的公司进行的为期一年的研究的新发现。在设定每周工作 32 小时的六个月后，参与者表示幸福感和工作满意度总体提高，并在六个月后仍高于基线水平。报告中的公司和工人对这些试验给予积极评价，大多数人表示他们希望继续每周工作四天。 （至关重要的是，员工的工资与工作时间较长时的工资相同。）报告指出，参与的公司“没有被要求制定特定类型的每周工作 4 天的制度”。<br><br>斯坦福大学研究工作的经济学家尼克·布鲁姆（Nick Bloom）在一封电子邮件中告诉我，《4 Day Week Global》最近的报告提出了有趣的问题。然而，对缩短周数的好处持怀疑态度的人正在等待更强有力的独立研究。现在，布鲁姆正在每周四天的时间里收集自己的调查数据。<br><br>布鲁姆指出，早在 1930 年，经济学家约翰·梅纳德·凯恩斯就预测工人可能会转向每周工作 15 小时。当时，许多美国人每周工作 50 小时。在大萧条时期，每周工作 40 小时成为常态，并最终于 1940 年被写入法律。后来， <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.washingtonpost.com/archive/politics/1978/05/20/pushing-for-a-shorter-work-week/5b3c4505-07ba-439a-bb62-97e18b821535/">工会领导人</a>和<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.nytimes.com/1956/09/23/archives/nixon-foresees-4day-work-week-says-gop-policies-assure-fuller-life.html">理查德·尼克松总统</a>预测每周工作时间甚至会更短。但在过去的几十年里，包括美国人<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2019/02/religion-workism-making-americans-miserable/583441/">对工作的崇拜</a>和<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.nytimes.com/2019/11/08/business/four-day-work-week.html">简单的惯性在内</a>的各种因素导致大多数公司都坚持标准的40小时工作时间。<br><br>只有正确实施，每周工作四天才能带来进步。对于那些一开始就需要承担难以管理的工作量的员工来说，试图在更短的时间内完成工作可能会导致倦怠。员工如何度过下班时间也很重要。如果员工周五在公园放松或与家人共度时光，很容易看出他们周一回来时会精神焕发、充满活力。但如果一名员工在周五<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.wired.com/story/four-day-week-burnout/">回复未缩短日程的客户的电子邮件</a>，情况可能并非如此。<br><br>英国萨塞克斯大学职业和组织心理学副教授、 <a data-event-element="inline link" href="http://www.agilab.org.uk/">agiLab</a>主任艾玛·拉塞尔 (Emma Russell) 表示，为了让每周四天的休假变得有益，员工需要知道他们的休假时间确实是属于自己的。我在电子邮件中。拉塞尔指出，面临经济不稳定的工人也可能会利用额外的时间从事另一份工作，如果他们因兼职而精疲力尽，他们可能无法获得主要工作时间减少所带来的健康回报。她补充说，对于公司来说，实施缩短工期的一刀切解决方案可能并不具有普遍帮助，因为工人有不同的责任和需求。<br><br> 4 Day Week Global 首席执行官 Dale Whelehan 承认，缩短周数并不一定是万能药。公司也需要接受重新思考工作负载的想法。 “这不仅仅是减少工作时间。它完全重新安排了你的工作方式、工作原因以及工作方式，”他告诉我。惠赫兰认为，许多人实际上已经在五个工作日的工作时间内完成了四天的工作，因为他们的工作效率没有达到应有的水平。对他来说，每周工作四天是公司更聪明地工作的一种方式，而不是假设每周工作五天的任意标准是最好的。<br><br>这一信息可能会受到那些渴望混合事物并重新构想组织的高管的欢迎。但对于那些已经<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.nytimes.com/2023/02/22/business/four-day-workweek-study.html">竭尽全力</a>提高效率的公司来说，这可能会让人感到侮辱。正如 Bloom 在他的电子邮件中所说，“我怀疑我们是否可以减少 20% 的工作时间并生产出相同的产品，否则我们早就做到了。”<br><br> “没有人喜欢工作，”他用笑脸表情符号补充道。<br><br><b>有关的：</b><br><br><li><a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/family/archive/2021/06/four-day-workweek/619222/">取消每周五天的工作制。</a></li><li> <a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2019/02/religion-workism-making-americans-miserable/583441/">工作主义正在让美国人痛苦不堪。</a></li><strong>今日新闻</strong><br><br><li>随着法律挑战的继续，最高法院<a href="https://www.nytimes.com/2023/08/08/us/supreme-court-biden-ghost-guns.html">暂时允许</a>拜登政府对“幽灵枪”进行限制，这些“幽灵枪”可以制成无法追踪的自制武器。</li><li>州长罗恩·德桑蒂斯 (Ron DeSantis) <a href="https://www.cnn.com/2023/08/08/politics/desantis-campaign-manager-replacement/index.html">已更换了</a>2024 年总统竞选经理，试图重拾势头。</li><li>洛杉矶超过 11,000 名市政工人<a href="https://www.washingtonpost.com/business/2023/08/08/los-angeles-municipal-strike/">参加了</a>今年夏天的一系列劳工行动。</li><b>晚读</b><br><br>解决当地新闻危机出奇地容易<br><br><em>史蒂文·沃尔德曼</em><br><br><p>扎克·波德莫尔并没有打倒腐败的市长。他没有发现秘密酷刑场所或揭露强大宗教机构的虐待行为。但他在 2019 年作为<i>《盐湖论坛报》</i>记者撰写的这篇文章改变了我对当地新闻价值的看法。</p><p>波德莫尔当时是《<i>论坛报》</i>的记者，也是我共同创办的非营利组织“美国报告”的一名成员，他发表了一篇报道，<a href="https://www.sltrib.com/news/2019/07/28/san-juan-county-paid/">揭露</a>犹他州圣胡安县向一家律师事务所支付了数十万美元的游说费。 Podmore 发现该公司向该州最贫困的县多收了 109,500 美元的费用。在他的故事的刺激下，该公司偿还了这笔钱。也许是因为它涉及的不是数十亿美元，而是一个更容易想象的数字，这让我震惊：在一个故事中，波德莫尔为县里收回了一笔相当于他年薪三倍的金额。</p> <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2023/08/local-news-investment-economic-value/674942/">阅读全文。</a><br><br><b>更多来自<em>大西洋月刊</em></b><br><br><li><a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/health/archive/2023/08/sweat-perspiration-evolution-human-function/674951/">我们必须学会热爱我们的汗水。</a></li><li><a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/international/archive/2023/08/niger-coup-russia/674947/">尼日尔的政变是关于权力的。俄罗斯将利用它。</a></li><li><a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/photo/2023/08/photos-18-months-war-ukraine/674953/">照片：乌克兰18个月的战争</a></li><b>文化突破</b><br><br><b>读。</b>詹姆斯·麦克布莱德的新小说《 <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://tertulia.com/book/the-heaven--earth-grocery-store-james-mcbride/9780593422946?affiliate_id=atl-347"><i>天堂与地球杂货店》</i></a>讲述了<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/magazine/archive/2023/09/the-heaven-earth-grocery-store-james-mcbride-book/674767/">黑人和犹太社区之间团结的故事</a>。<br><br><b>手表。</b>酷儿戏剧<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://mubi.com/en/r/passages"><i>《Passages》</i></a> （现已上映）是一部关于<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/culture/archive/2023/08/passages-movie-review/674910/">打破常规的</a>风流韵事的电影。<br><br><a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/free-daily-crossword-puzzle/">玩我们的日常填字游戏。</a><br><br> <i>Katherine Hu为本期通讯做出了贡献。</i><br><br><em>当您使用本新闻通讯中的链接购买书籍时，我们会收到佣金。感谢您对大西洋月刊的支持</em><em>。</em><br><br></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Tue, 08 Aug 2023 23:25:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.theatlantic.com/newsletters/archive/2023/08/four-day-workweek-hours/674960/</guid><link/> https://www.theatlantic.com/newsletters/archive/2023/08/four-day-workweek-hours/674960/ </item><item><title><![CDATA[I’m Supporting Colombia Now]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>就其电动风格以及其球员为进入女足世界杯所克服的一切而言，这是理所当然的。 <br><figure><img src="https://cdn.theatlantic.com/thumbor/TWooRl9bCWX25OvfVb8kHplYDyE=/0x0:4800x2700/960x540/media/img/mt/2023/08/fifa_world_cup/original.jpg" alt="哥伦比亚的琳达·凯塞多和四名牙买加球员一起参加了女足世界杯的比赛" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><figcaption> Asanka Brendon Ratnayake / 路透社</figcaption></figure>宿命论可能是粉丝最好的朋友。当美国女队开始本届世界杯时，我希望最好的事情发生，但我的大脑不断警告我，这支球队注定会遇到最坏的情况。令人痛苦的是，球队没有得到很好的训练，关键球员的受伤导致球队无法克服糟糕的战术。从第一场比赛开始，我观看了比赛的其余部分，寻找另一个国家，如果美国队熄火的话，我可以采用这个国家作为我自己的国家。<br><br>西班牙以其复杂的传球和时尚的控球能力引起了我的注意。作为一名亲英人士，我对英格兰队很感兴趣，直到英格兰球星劳伦·詹姆斯（Lauren James） <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.foxnews.com/sports/england-star-lauren-james-gets-red-card-violent-conduct-egregious-act-nigeria">鲁莽地</a>将球鞋插入倒地的尼日利亚球员米歇尔·阿洛齐（Michelle Alozie）的背部，而英格兰队则急忙缓和了进攻。但现在美国队已经退出世界杯，每个中立的善意球迷都应该热烈支持这个国家，因为它的电动风格和球员们努力克服的一切。那支球队是哥伦比亚。<br><br>尽管人们很容易赞扬<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/culture/archive/2023/07/womens-world-cup-2023-nwsl-megan-rapinoe-alyssa-thompson/674816/">女子运动的进步</a>以及美国女性在争取同工同酬方面取得的成功，但许多国家仍然以令人震惊的方式对待她们的女运动员。哥伦比亚可以说是记录在案的最令人震惊的例子。<br><br>由于该国中场球员丹妮拉·蒙托亚的勇敢，我们对此了解很多。 2015年女足世界杯期间，她的球队晋级16强，这对于刚刚起步的哥伦比亚女足来说是一项令人难以置信的成就。她的队友不仅没有获得同工同酬，而且还未能获得同等报酬。 <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://globalsportmatters.com/culture/2023/06/28/colombian-national-womens-football-team-crisis/">据报道，他们根本没有得到</a>任何报酬，只是得到一点费用帮助。当蒙托亚向媒体抱怨时，她的国家足协拒绝了她参加 2016 年夏季奥运会的名单。后来，她<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.reuters.com/article/us-soccer-usa-colombia/women-footballers-in-colombia-revolt-over-mistreatment-idUSKBN1QQ0F1">挥舞着</a>一名哥伦比亚足球官员的音频片段，据称解释说她因鲁莽开口而受到惩罚。<br><br>这种工资盗窃现象在哥伦比亚比赛中十分猖獗。一支女子球队，Atlético Huila，赢得了南美大陆俱乐部冠军——解放者杯。球员们被告知，他们的胜利将总共获得约 55,000 美元的奖金。但球队的奖金<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://globalsportmatters.com/culture/2023/06/28/colombian-national-womens-football-team-crisis/">显然被支付</a>给了一位为球队提供资金的商人。和蒙托亚一样，向媒体提出这些抱怨的球员也被排除在国家队名单之外，尽管她所施加的压力迫使俱乐部最终给了这些女性承诺的奖励。<br><br>这些事件只会增加官方的一系列不尊重行为：球员们<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://assembly.malala.org/stories/colombian-womens-soccer">抱怨</a>国家足协让他们支付自己的国际航班费用，甚至不给他们买新<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.reuters.com/article/us-soccer-usa-colombia/women-footballers-in-colombia-revolt-over-mistreatment-idUSKBN1QQ0F1">球衣</a>。哥伦比亚俱乐部的一位有权有势的老板，同时也是该国参议院的成员，曾将女子比赛<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://as.com/futbol/2018/12/20/internacional/1545338936_774939.html">描述</a>为“女同性恋的培养皿”。<br><br>情况变得更糟。代表哥伦比亚参加国际青年锦标赛的 U-17 国家队技术总监据称虐待队内的女孩。根据 2019 年提出的<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://colombiareports.com/amp/womens-football-in-colombia-harassment-blackmail-and-sexual-assault-of-minors/">指控</a>，他对这些青少年进行了不当触摸、向他们求爱，并未经他们同意进入他们的酒店房间。 （亚利桑那州立大学的一个项目“全球体育事务”在一份出色的<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://globalsportmatters.com/culture/2023/06/28/colombian-national-womens-football-team-crisis/">报告</a>中对此进行了叙述。）再次，发声的球员被排除在国家队之外。技术总监同意认罪交易，承认减少了指控，但逃脱了牢狱之灾。<br><br>尽管如此，在今年的世界杯上，哥伦比亚女足当之无愧地击败了世界排名第二的德国队。他们刚刚淘汰了牙买加队，晋级四分之一决赛，周六他们将对阵实力耗尽的英格兰队。<br><br>哥伦比亚队令人兴奋的核心是 18 岁的攻击手琳达·凯塞多 (Linda Caicedo)，她是本届锦标赛的亮点，现在经常被誉为有潜力成为足球史上最伟大的球员之一。她可以运球击败一大群防守者，也可以用突破线的传球撕开防守。 （她对德国队的<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=5KdC3RiEnY4">进球</a>展现了无可挑剔的步法，是迄今为止比赛中最好的进球之一。）<br><br> <a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/culture/archive/2023/08/us-womens-national-team-soccer-world-cup/674885/">阅读：美国女足统治地位的终结</a><br><br>即使她没有那么才华横溢，单凭她的传记就足以令人着迷。 15岁时，她被诊断出患有卵巢癌，需要手术。尽管身患疾病且年事已高，她仍继续<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.npr.org/2023/08/02/1191392108/colombia-linda-caicedo-world-cup">批评</a>她的雇主哥伦比亚足协对待球队的恶劣态度。她的技术显然非常出色，以至于西班牙超级俱乐部皇家马德里将她转移到了迅速进步的女足球队中。尽管如此，从凯塞多的病史来看，她的脆弱感始终存在。上周，在哥伦比亚队与德国队的比赛之前，一段视频拍摄到她在训练中突然倒地，脸朝下躺在草地上，医护人员赶来救她。团队的官方解释是疲劳，但这一集抓住了崇高的完美和偶然性的结合，使凯塞多成为一个令人同情且最终不可抗拒的主角。<br><br>哥伦比亚队的表现最令人兴奋的也许是它与球迷的联系。前往澳大利亚和新西兰的哥伦比亚队伍是本届赛事规模最大、声音最大的队伍之一。这本身就是一项成就：尽管她们在途中遇到了业主和官员的阻挠，但妇女们还是成功地赢得了她们的同胞的支持。从某种意义上说，这使她们成为美国女性的真正继承人，她们在巅峰时期也凭借勇敢的行动主义和球场上的卓越表现改变了公众舆论。美国人，拥抱哥伦比亚队就像拥抱自己的球队一样。<br><br></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Tue, 08 Aug 2023 22:22:38 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.theatlantic.com/culture/archive/2023/08/us-womens-world-cup-colombia/674958/</guid><link/> https://www.theatlantic.com/culture/archive/2023/08/us-womens-world-cup-colombia/674958/ </item><item><title><![CDATA[Welcome to the Age of ‘Foomscrolling’]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div> LK-99 和 ChatGPT 引发的网络狂热揭示了技术乐观主义的复苏，以及对新技术的共同渴望，这种新技术将使我们摆脱人类的限制。 <br><figure><img src="https://cdn.theatlantic.com/thumbor/yP3vUxT9CICFGM-CAF-gr3x3Fo4=/0x0:4800x2700/960x540/media/img/mt/2023/08/lk_99_foomscroll_/original.jpg" alt="许多手机的插图，每部手机都显示一个漂浮的“LK99”肿块的图像" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><figcaption>大西洋月刊插图。资料来源：盖蒂。</figcaption></figure>我记得第一次看到漂浮的岩石时的情景。那是半夜，我面临着失眠者的困境：要不要去拿电话。我到达并打开了 Twitter——那是两周前的事了； <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/technology/archive/2023/07/twitter-x-rebrand-juvenile-internet-style/674875/">新名字</a>还没有被人们所接受——理论上来说，滚动浏览我的提要可能会达到某种催眠效果，为睡眠创造一个机会。就在那时我看到了模糊的<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://sciencecast.org/casts/suc384jly50n">视频</a>。其中，一块小而畸形的材料碎片，像铅笔折断的铅尖一样，神秘地悬浮在厚厚的抛光金属晶片上方。<br><br>我直接滚动过去。尽管关注了相当多的“纯粹的科学事物”聚合器，但在凌晨时分，我并不总是对启发感到兴奋。但几分钟后，我又看到了这个视频，然后是第三次。我注意到这不是对磁力的说教解释。这是新闻：漂浮的岩石是 LK-99，一种由韩国科学家团队合成的物质，他们认为它是一种室温环境压力超导体。<br><br>我想告诉大家，那天晚上<em>“室温常压超导体”</em>这个词对我来说很有意义，但没有。我对这句话感到困惑，就像猿猴审视着一块巨石。我寻找上下文线索。我数了数感叹号。经过几分钟的内心抵制后，我做了一些尽职调查，我的意思是轻松而睡眼惺忪地谷歌搜索。最终，通过一些努力，我了解到 LK-99 可能是材料科学家的圣杯发现。<br><br>但不仅仅是材料科学家！这与 2020 年在金星大气层中<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/science/archive/2020/09/venus-life-phosphine-microbes/616342/">观测</a>到的磷化氢不同。如果这一发现成立（可惜<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.science.org/content/article/potential-signs-life-venus-are-fading-astronomers-downgrade-their-original-claims">事实并非如此</a>），它将强烈表明该行星上存在生命，这是一项划时代的发现，但不会改变我们的世界。室温超导体的存在不仅仅是一个关于自然的新事实。相反，根据<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://theconversation.com/room-temperature-superconductors-could-revolutionize-electronics-an-electrical-engineer-explains-the-materials-potential-201849">一些</a>观察家的说法，这意味着我们可以获得一种神奇的、万能的物质，它可以将我们带入一个新技术时代，电力在我们的世界中<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://theconversation.com/how-do-superconductors-work-a-physicist-explains-what-it-means-to-have-resistance-free-electricity-202308">毫无摩擦地</a>流动，更多的计算机是<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://thequantuminsider.com/2023/08/03/how-would-room-temperature-superconductors-change-quantum-computing/">量子的</a>，火车也是如此，很<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.nature.com/articles/d41586-023-02481-0">飘逸</a>。<br><br>鉴于 LK-99 据称是进口的，一场<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/science/archive/2023/08/lk99-superconductors-floating-rocks/674939/">复制韩国研究结果的</a>全球竞赛已经开始，互联网上的许多人都兴奋地观看着。中国首先到达那里的幽灵增添了一层地缘政治阴谋。 （我喜欢想象美国的材料科学家挤在一起，准备迎接他们的人造卫星时刻。） 与此同时， <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theverge.com/23820077/lk-99-superconductor-experts">据报道</a>韩国科学家之间也存在<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.newscientist.com/article/2384782-room-temperature-superconductor-breakthrough-met-with-scepticism/?utm_source=rakuten&amp;utm_medium=affiliate&amp;utm_campaign=2116208:Skimlinks.com&amp;utm_content=10&amp;ranMID=47192&amp;ranEAID=TnL5HPStwNw&amp;ranSiteID=TnL5HPStwNw-w0iN0psrMFqpajHAWVaDMA">争执</a>。每个人都可以在社交媒体上关注，惊叹于每块悬浮的岩石，就像 Twitch 观众惊叹于游戏玩家最新的击杀镜头一样。如果不出意外的话，这是一种打发时间的好方法，直到一个闪闪发光的科技乌托邦在我们周围实现。<br><br> <a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/science/archive/2023/08/lk99-superconductors-floating-rocks/674939/">阅读：浮石的重要一周</a><br><br>明确地说，我所描述的是我所经历过的 LK-99 周围的氛围。最接近的类似可能是去年 11 月 ChatGPT 发布时的狂热。也许您还记得：大流行晚期的不适正在逐渐消退；人们已经准备好接受闪亮的新事物；然后，突然间，这些东西以机器人的形式出现，它们可以聊天、编码，甚至可能破坏你的婚姻。社交媒体上充斥着他们最聪明、最狡猾的攻击行为的屏幕截图<em>。</em><br><br>在 ChatGPT 发布后的几个月里，一些人开始相信正在发生“<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://en.wiktionary.org/wiki/foom">爆炸</a>”。在人工智能文献中，当人工智能的级联自我改进加速其自身发展，直至其变得强大到超出人类理解范围时，就会出现繁荣。 （这个词的意思是让人想起爆炸性喷发的声音。）这种特殊的、所谓的爆炸的巧妙之处在于：它是实时体验的，至少对于那些足够在线的人来说是这样。我们被<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://a16z.com/2023/06/06/ai-will-save-the-world/">告知，</a>技术即将让我们摆脱痛苦和匮乏，你可以在 Twitter 上看到这一切。在特朗普担任总统期间，创造了<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/doomscrolling-the-new-high-tech-way-to-slide-into-despair-11607640701"><em>“doomscrolling”</em></a>这个词来描述通过智能手机发布坏消息的习惯。这是不同的；它具有正价。称之为 fooscrolling。<br><br>并非所有新兴技术都会导致 fooscrolling。当它的非凡力量可以通过一些立即可识别的视觉形式（例如双音聊天屏幕截图或漂浮的岩石）来展示时，这种行为就更有可能发生。更重要的是，要获得 Foomscrolling 的资格，新兴技术必须是能够合理提升物种水平的技术。 （阿波罗任务会导致无休止的滚动；想象一下，<em>地出</em>照片有 100 万次转发，<span class="smallcaps">标题是我们回来了</span>。）GLP-1 受体激活药物，比如 Ozempic 中的药物，提供了一个有启发性的反例。尽管构成了人们期待已久的奇迹——一种<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.statnews.com/2023/08/08/novo-nordisk-wegovy-cardiovascular-risk/">有效</a>的减肥药——但它们只能解决某些问题<em>。</em>没有人发帖称这些药物最终将解决气候变化问题； Ozempic 不会提示任何人进行 fooscroll。<br><br> <a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/health/archive/2023/06/ozempic-pills-obesity-drugs-semaglutide/674541/">阅读：再见，臭氧</a><br><br>就人工智能而言，快速滚动很快就变成了一种自嘲的东西：人工智能影响者的家庭手工业。他们支付了蓝色支票和个人简历，小心翼翼地洗白了他们之前对加密货币的热情。最初，它们很有用。该领域发展迅速，有一些行业新闻聚合器是件好事，尽管有些人容易轻信。但他们很快就声称本周令人心碎的突破清单比上周更广泛，从而压倒了讨论。这一切开始显得有点悲伤，就像 LinkedIn 一样。<br><br>也许这只是 fooscrolling 循环。最近几天，LK-99 粉丝群体一直处于不利地位。 <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2023-08-08/superconductor-lk-99-sample-may-be-available-in-weeks">通货紧缩现实主义</a>的光环已经开始为这个故事增添色彩。一些评论家声称 LK-99 只是一种<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://twitter.com/alexkaplan0/status/1688734992682086400">铁磁体</a>，科学家们已经得到消息，即使这种物质确实是室温超导体，通往<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://knowyourmeme.com/memes/the-world-if">“社会将如何看待”模因</a>中描绘的未来之路也将是漫长的。一。复制声明不再是我的“为你”提要的首要内容。细微差别和清醒似乎赢得了胜利。<br><br>超导滚动的顶峰可能已经过去了。但推动它的文化欲望——对一种新工具的渴望，能够帮助我们摆脱人性的弱点，走上某种平稳的指数轨迹，通向闪闪发光和不朽的未来——看起来相当有弹性。这种集体渴望可能从奥杜瓦伊以来就以这样或那样的形式伴随着我们。互联网只是将其放大为一种探照灯。我想象它的光束很快就会找到其他东西来锁定，世界上的失眠症患者可以在夜深人静的时候用谷歌搜索一些新的东西，希望这一次，繁荣将是真实的。<br><br></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Tue, 08 Aug 2023 20:47:40 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.theatlantic.com/technology/archive/2023/08/foomscrolling-ai-chatgpt-lk-99-superconductor/674955/</guid><link/> https://www.theatlantic.com/technology/archive/2023/08/foomscrolling-ai-chatgpt-lk-99-superconductor/674955/ </item><item><title><![CDATA[When Small-Town Pride Sounds Like Anger]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>贾森·阿尔丁 (Jason Aldean) 说“在小镇尝试一下”庆祝社区，但它的文字和声音讲述了一个不同的故事。 <br><figure><img src="https://cdn.theatlantic.com/thumbor/1YzXZDhaMJq9PEm5-Zi9uBQNyW8=/0x0:4800x2700/960x540/media/img/mt/2023/08/country_2/original.jpg" alt="乡村歌手摩根·沃伦（左）、杰森·阿尔丁（中）和卢克·库姆斯的拼贴画" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><figcaption> 《大西洋月刊》的照片插图。资料来源：埃德·罗德/盖蒂；约翰希勒/盖蒂；迈克尔·洛西萨诺/盖蒂。</figcaption></figure><small><em>更新于 2023 年 8 月 8 日东部时间下午 3:52。</em></small><br><br>乡村音乐是一种具有百年历史的怀旧、传统和乡音音乐流派，其风格从未如此流行。上周，<em>公告牌</em>百强单曲榜历史上<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.billboard.com/music/chart-beat/jason-aldean-try-that-in-a-small-town-number-one-hot-100-country-hits-top-three-1235382220/">首次</a>出现美国最受欢迎的三首乡村歌曲。对于这一里程碑的一个解释是，该流派的艺术家和观众最终<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.billboard.com/pro/country-music-consumption-up-2023-morgan-wallen/">倾向于</a><a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://variety.com/2023/music/news/cmts-morgan-wallen-country-streaming-march-1235573629/">流媒体</a>：今年，乡村音乐的听众人数增长了 20%，增幅仅次于拉丁音乐和韩国流行音乐。<br><br>但这是一场值得庆祝的奇怪胜利，不仅因为上周排名第一的歌曲杰森·阿尔丁（Jason Aldean）的《在小镇尝试》（Try That in a Small Town）已被证明是一个政治热点。现在突破的曲目每首听起来都不像<em>乡村</em>音乐。这种流派总是传达出一定程度的失败者的反抗，但最近，音乐和围绕它的对话有一种明显的怨恨色彩。<br><br>在《在小镇尝试一下》中，46 岁的佐治亚州流行音乐制作人阿尔丁向所谓的乡村价值观（荣誉、邻里关系、拥有枪支）致敬，警告听众所谓的城市病态（抢劫、向警察吐口水、焚烧旗帜） ）不要乘坐某些人所说的“ <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/national/archive/2016/06/a-note-about-trumpism-from-the-real-america/623689/">真正的美国</a>”。 “在这里，我们照顾自己的事情，”他夸口道。但音乐很难让人想起宁静的牧场或布满锯末的酒吧。当我听到这首歌中低沉的吉他声、低沉的小和弦以及从 Foo Fighters 的《Everlong》中摘录的即兴重复段时，我感觉自己回到了 2000 年左右的郊区男性青春期——那时我穿着一件超大的黑色连帽衫，聆听带有灵魂补丁的男人的呻吟。 Aldean 的歌曲名义上是乡村歌曲，但其声音却是后垃圾摇滚另类摇滚。<br><br> 90 年代初，Nirvana 及其同侪为一种新的主​​流男子气概开辟了空间：容易受到失败和疏远感的影响，但又带有一种硬朗、嘈杂的边缘，没有人会认为这是<em>娘娘腔</em>。很快，一群<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/magazine/archive/2018/07/linkin-park-chester-bennington/561713/">旋律优美的</a>乐队出现了，比如 Bush、Creed 和 Nickelback，他们剪掉了朋克风格中的垃圾摇滚，为漫无目的的焦虑创造了一个广泛吸引人的模板。现在，阿尔丁用踏板钢和右翼谈话要点更新了该模板。<br><br>你可能听说过<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/politics/archive/2023/07/jason-aldean-donald-trump/674842/">这首歌是有争议的</a>。阿尔丁设置了一个完美的话语陷阱，利用了美国当前在<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2019/12/historians-clash-1619-project/604093/">其自身历史的两种理论</a>之间的分裂，以及强烈反对与反对之间循环的可预测性和盈利能力。尽管这首歌没有提及种族，但许多听众在其中听到了狗哨声：阿尔丁歌词所认可的“好男孩”私刑主义在历史上一直与<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/national/archive/2022/02/america-lynching-history-reckoning/621320/">白人至上主义暴力</a>联系在一起。 His music video included images of Black Lives Matter protesters (though that footage was <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.washingtonpost.com/arts-entertainment/2023/07/25/jason-aldean-controversial-music-video-edited/">later edited out</a> ), and was shot in front of a Tennessee courthouse where a Black man was lynched in 1927. (The production company that made the video told <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.washingtonpost.com/entertainment/music/2023/07/20/jason-aldean-song-video-pulled-cmt-controversy/"><em>The Washington Post</em></a> that it had chosen a “popular filming location outside of Nashville.”) But critiques of the song have only amplified it: After Country Music Television banned the video, the track&#39;s streams <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theguardian.com/music/2023/jul/24/jason-aldean-small-town-song-streaming-increase">shot up 999 percent</a> .<br><br> <a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/entertainment/archive/2018/04/jason-aldean-rearview-town-las-vegas/557876/">Read: Music that mourns, whether it wants to or not</a><br><br> Aldean professes mystification at the dustup he&#39;s provoked. The song, he <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://twitter.com/Jason_Aldean/status/1681382697875144717?lang=en">has said</a> , simply “refers to the feeling of a community that I had growing up.” (Aldean, for what it&#39;s worth, grew up in the midsize city of Macon, Georgia.) This insistence, more than the southern lilt of Aldean&#39;s voice, makes the track <em>country</em> . Aldean is working in a tradition of music that disses cities while celebrating rural can-do. But he&#39;s not singing with the wry, plucky tone of Merle Haggard&#39;s “Okie From Muskogee” or even with the gruff confidence of Hank Williams Jr.&#39;s “A Country Boy Can Survive.” Nor is he delivering provocative slogans with the <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/magazine/archive/2017/11/toby-keith-the-bus-songs/540654/">rock-star panache of Toby Keith</a> . Rather, Aldean sounds wallowing and fearful in that distinctly post-grunge way—even as his words profess action.<br><br> Perhaps that vibe of sublimated anxiety reflects the tragedy underlying the song: small-town America&#39;s decades-long economic decline. The big-city problems Aldean laments— <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.thirdway.org/report/the-two-decade-red-state-murder-problem">violent crime</a> , <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.washingtonpost.com/magazine/2022/05/23/how-my-hometown-produced-jan-6-sedition-suspect/">sedition</a> , even <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/business/archive/2017/10/small-town-economies-culture/543138/">fraying communal ties</a> —are, in many cases, worse problems outside the cities than in them. This reality is a major driver of right-wing resentment—and music about it should, by all rights, have a hint of malaise. Aldean was previously known for anthems of carefree country living (although his 2018 single “Rearview Town” did almost seem like a dirge for rural dreams, it was actually a breakup song). A better precedent for “Small Town” is Staind&#39;s 2001 hit, “It&#39;s Been Awhile”: “It&#39;s been a while / Since I could hold my head up high.” Not coincidentally, Staind&#39;s Aaron Lewis is now a popular country musician—and one of the <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.miamiherald.com/news/nation-world/national/article252897928.html">most effective right-wing protest singers in memory</a> .<br><br> It&#39;s also not a coincidence that Morgan Wallen—currently the most popular country artist by a wide margin, and the singer of “Last Night,” last week&#39;s No. 2 song on the Hot 100—is a spiritual child of Nickelback. The Canadian rock band, famous for the catchy aughts rumble of “How You Remind Me” and “Photograph,” is often mocked <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/national/archive/2012/09/rahm-emanuel-saves-reputation-renounces-nickelback/323749/">as the ultimate example of musical blandness</a> . But Wallen has unapologetically cited the group as an influence. His go-to producer, Joey Moi, produced many of Nickelback&#39;s early-2000s hits, including “Photograph”—and then co-founded Big Loud, which is now one of the hottest labels in Nashville.<br><br> <a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/culture/archive/2020/07/country-music-pandemic-protests-the-chicks-gaslighter/614092/">Read: Country music can no longer hide its problems</a><br><br> A 30-year-old former contestant on <em>The Voice</em> , Wallen is a serious pop talent, and “Last Night”—a sensation since its release in February—is excellent (which explains why it replaced Aldean&#39;s track at the top of the Hot 100 today). There&#39;s a bit of a Nickelback quality to the laminated nature of the production, and the way that the singer conveys a light hatred of himself, but “Last Night” mostly exemplifies a separate trend in Nashville: so-called hick-hop, modern country influenced by rap. Singing in a sassy twang about drunken fighting and reconciliation, over a brisk guitar loop and handclaps that form a syncopated beat, Wallen emanates the same sleazy charm as Drake. The irony here is obvious: In 2021, Wallen was caught saying the N-word on camera, which resulted in a supposed “cancellation” that, like Aldean&#39;s, only boosted his <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/culture/archive/2021/02/morgan-wallen/618137/">listenership</a> .<br><br> Last week&#39;s No. 3 song in the nation, Luke Combs&#39;s take on Tracy Chapman&#39;s “Fast Car,” has created a little controversy as well. It is basically a note-for-note cover of a 1988 classic, differentiated mostly by the gruff beauty of Combs&#39;s voice. After it began to rise in the charts last month, some commentators <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.washingtonpost.com/arts-entertainment/2023/07/13/tracy-chapman-luke-combs-fast-car-cover/">pointed out</a> that neither Chapman nor any other Black woman had ever had the kind of success in country music that Combs is enjoying. This observation sparked <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.foxnews.com/opinion/greg-gutfeld-another-week-another-country-music-star-falsely-accused-racism">conservative annoyance</a> louder than the original critique, likely boosting the song&#39;s popularity. As my colleague Conor Friedersdorf <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/newsletters/archive/2023/07/why-is-tracy-chapman-at-the-center-of-a-country-music-controversy/674794/">argues</a> , the discourse around the song demonstrates how media coverage of race can inspire more confusion than reform.<br><br> But is it tenable to ask observers of this authenticity-minded, all-American genre to avoid speaking about conspicuous truths? The reality of country music&#39;s <em>Billboard</em> Hot 100 takeover this past week is glaring. The music is diverse, but the performers aren&#39;t: Between Aldean&#39;s protest rock, Wallen&#39;s laid-back rap flow, and Combs&#39;s soul-folk cover, this boom for mainstream country is rooted not in sound but in white, male, and—at least in Aldean&#39;s case—aggrieved identity. Of course, all genres are defined by demographics. But streaming technology, not to mention social and political media, now rewards the inflaming of passionate pluralities, including by sowing division. Inflaming stan versus stan, or right versus left, can prove profitable—at least for a short while (Aldean&#39;s song today fell from No. 1 to No. 21 on the Hot 100).<br><br> Artists in other genres are going to learn lessons from this boomlet. Just a few days ago, Aldean made a surprise appearance at a Nickelback concert in Nashville. Nickelback&#39;s front man, Chad Kroeger, has never been known for his political outspokenness. But that night, he <a data-event-element="inline link" href="http://tennessean.com/story/entertainment/music/2023/08/02/jason-aldean-appears-with-brantley-gilbert-at-nashville-nickelback-concert/70511233007/">made a speech</a> : For 20 years, he said, “they&#39;ve been trying to cancel us.”<br><br> <small><em>This story originally misstated when Tracy Chapman&#39;s “Fast Car” was released.</em></small><br><br></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Tue, 08 Aug 2023 16:10:29 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.theatlantic.com/culture/archive/2023/08/jason-aldean-country-music-luke-combs/674952/</guid><link/> https://www.theatlantic.com/culture/archive/2023/08/jason-aldean-country-music-luke-combs/674952/ </item><item><title><![CDATA[We Must Learn to Love Our Sweat]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div> The world is getting hotter. Prepare to be damp. <br><figure><img src="https://cdn.theatlantic.com/thumbor/hTAgCxxbllf10_DEjIQv7unZQPU=/912x514:3839x2160/960x540/media/img/mt/2023/08/sweat1/original.jpg" alt="Close-up photograph of someone wiping their sweaty brow" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><figcaption> Getty</figcaption></figure> This summer, I, like so many other Americans, have forgotten what it means to be dry. The heat has grown so punishing, and the humidity so intense, that every movement sends my body into revolt. When I stand, I sweat. When I sit, I sweat. When I slice into a particularly dense head of cabbage, I sweat.<br><br> The way things are going, infinite moistness may be something many of us will have to get used to. This past July was the world&#39;s hottest month in recorded history; off the coast of Florida, <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.npr.org/2023/07/26/1190218132/florida-ocean-temperatures-101-marine-life-damage">ocean temperatures</a> <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/science/archive/2023/08/marine-heat-waves-earth-climate-change/674892/">hit triple digits</a> , while in Arizona, the asphalt <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.nbcnews.com/science/science-news/heat-wave-second-third-degree-burns-illness-heat-exhaustion-rcna95107">caused</a> <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.cnn.com/2023/07/24/health/arizona-heat-burns-er/index.html">third-degree burns</a> . As human-driven climate change continues to remodel the globe, <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.nature.com/articles/s41467-020-16970-7">heat waves</a> are hitting <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://nap.nationalacademies.org/read/21852/chapter/6#90">harder, longer, and more frequently</a> . The consequences of this crisis will, on a macroscopic scale, upend where and how humans can survive. It will also, in an everyday sense, make our lives very, very sweaty.<br><br> For most Americans, that&#39;s probably unwelcome news. Our culture <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.smithsonianmag.com/history/how-advertisers-convinced-americans-they-smelled-bad-12552404/">doesn&#39;t exactly love sweat</a> . Heavy perspirers are shunned on subways; BO is a hallmark of pubescent shame. History is splattered with examples of people trying to cloak sweat in perfumes, wash it away by bathing, or soak it up with wads of <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.smithsonianmag.com/history/how-advertisers-convinced-americans-they-smelled-bad-12552404/">cotton or rubber</a> crammed into their shirts, dresses, and hats. People without medical reason to do so have opted to paralyze their sweat-triggering nerves with Botox. Even Bruce Lee had the sweat glands in his armpits <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC9664576/">surgically removed</a> , reportedly to avoid on-screen stains, several months before his death, in 1973.<br><br> But our scorn of sweat is entirely undeserved. Perspiration is vital to life. It cools our bodies and hydrates our skin; it manages our microbiome and emits chemical cues. Sweat is also a fundamental part of what makes people <em>people</em> . Without it, we wouldn&#39;t be able to <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/abs/pii/S0047248417303652?via%3Dihub">run long distances</a> in high heat; we wouldn&#39;t be able to power our big brains and bodies; we wouldn&#39;t have colonized so much of the Earth. We may even have sweat to thank (or blame) for our skin&#39;s nakedness, says Yana Kamberov, a sweat researcher at the University of Pennsylvania. Her team&#39;s recent data, not yet published, suggest that as human skin evolved to produce more and more sweat glands, fur-making hair follicles disappeared to make room. Sweat is one of the “key milestones” in human evolution, argues Andrew Best, a biological anthropologist at the Massachusetts College of Liberal Arts—on par with big brains, walking upright, and the expression of culture through language and art.<br><br> Humans aren&#39;t the only animals that sweat. <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/abs/pii/S0047248417303652?via%3Dihub">Many mammals</a> —among them, dogs, cats, and rats—perspire through the footpads on their paws; chimpanzees, macaques, and other primates are covered in sweat glands. Even horses and camels slick their skin in the heat. But only our bodies are studded with this many millions of teeny, tubular sweat glands—about 10 times the number found on other primates&#39; skin—that funnel water from our blood to pores that can squeeze out <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK236237/">upwards of three, four</a> , <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.tandfonline.com/doi/full/10.1080/02640414.2019.1633159">even <em>five</em> liters of sweat an hour</a> when we need them to.<br><br> Our dampness isn&#39;t cost free. Sweat is siphoned from the liquid components of blood— <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/health/archive/2023/08/drinking-water-hydration-amount-importance/674926/">lose too much</a> , and the risks of heat stroke and death shoot way up. Our lack of fur also makes us more vulnerable to bites and burns. That humans sweat anyway, then, Best told me, is a testament to perspiration&#39;s cooling punch—it&#39;s so much more efficient than merely panting or hiding from the heat. “If your objective is to be able to sustain a high metabolic rate in warm conditions, sweating is absolutely <em>the best</em> ,” he said.<br><br> <a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/health/archive/2023/08/drinking-water-hydration-amount-importance/674926/">Read: You&#39;re probably drinking enough water</a><br><br> And yet, in modern times, many of us just can&#39;t seem to accept the realities of sweat. Americans are, for whatever reason, particularly preoccupied with quashing perspiration; in many other countries, “body odor is just normal,” says Angela Lamb, a dermatologist at Mount Sinai&#39;s Icahn School of Medicine. But the bemoaning of BO has cultural roots that long predate the United States. “I&#39;ve read discussions well back into antiquity where there are discussions about people whose armpits stink,” says Cari Casteel, a historian at the University of Buffalo. By the start of the 20th century, Americans had been primed by the recent popularization of germ theory to fear dirtiness—the perfect moment for marketers to “put the fear in women, and then men, that sweat was going to kibosh your plans for romance or a job,” says Sarah Everts, the author of <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://tertulia.com/book/the-joy-of-sweat-the-strange-science-of-perspiration-sarah-everts/9781324022060?affiliate_id=atl-347"><em>The Joy of Sweat</em></a> . These days, deodorants command an <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.mordorintelligence.com/industry-reports/north-america-deodorants-market">$8 billion market</a> in the United States.<br><br> Our aversion to sweat doesn&#39;t make much evolutionary sense. Unlike other excretions that elicit near-universal disgust, sweat doesn&#39;t routinely transmit disease or pose other harm. But it does evoke physical labor and emotional stress—neither of which polite society is typically keen to see. And for some, maybe it signifies “losing control of your body in a particular way,” says Tina Lasisi, a biological anthropologist at the University of Michigan. Unlike urine or tears, sweat is the product of a body function that we can&#39;t train ourselves to suppress or delay.<br><br> We also hate sweat because we think it smells bad. But it doesn&#39;t, really. Nearly all of the sweat glands on human bodies are of the so-called eccrine variety, and produce slightly salty water with virtually no scent. A few spots, such as the armpits and groin, are freckled with apocrine glands that produce a waxy, fatty substance laced with pheromones—but even <em>that</em> has no inherent odor. The bacteria on our skin eat it, and their waste generates a stench, leaving sweat as the scapegoat. Our species&#39; approach to perspiration may even make us “less stinky than we could be,” Best told me. The expansion of eccrine glands across the body might not have only made our skin barer; it&#39;s also thought to have <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/abs/pii/S0047248417303652?via%3Dihub">evicted a whole legion of BO-producing apocrine glands</a> .<br><br> As global temperatures climb, for many people—especially in parts of the world that lack access to air-conditioning—sweat will be an inevitability. “I suspect everyone is going to be quite drippy,” Kamberov told me. Exactly how slick each of us will be, though, is anyone&#39;s guess. Experts have evidence that <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://scholarworks.umass.edu/cgi/viewcontent.cgi?article=3328&amp;context=dissertations_2">men sweat more than women, and that perspiration potential declines with age</a> . But by and large, they can&#39;t say with certainty why some people are <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/abs/pii/S0306456519302645?via%3Dihub">inherently sweatier than others</a> , and how much of it is inborn. Decades ago, a Japanese researcher hypothesized that perspiration potential might be <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://linkinghub.elsevier.com/retrieve/pii/S0306456519302645">calibrated in the first two or three years of life</a> : Kids born into tropical climates, his analyses suggested, might activate more of their sweat glands than children in temperate regions. But Best&#39;s recent <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://onlinelibrary.wiley.com/doi/abs/10.1002/ajpa.24723">attempts</a> to replicate those findings have so far come up empty.<br><br> <a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/health/archive/2019/11/prince-andrew-says-he-once-didnt-sweat-is-that-possible/602227/">Read: The man who did not sweat</a><br><br> Perspiration does seem to be malleable within a lifetime. A <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/24692142/">couple of weeks</a> into a new, intense exercise regimen, for instance, people will start to sweat<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.cdc.gov/niosh/topics/heatstress/acclima.html">more and earlier</a> . Over longer periods of time, the body can also learn to tolerate high temperatures, and sweat less copiously but more <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://linkinghub.elsevier.com/retrieve/pii/S0306456519302645">efficiently</a> . We sense these changes subtly as the seasons shift, says Laure Rittié, a physiologist at Glaxo-Smith Kline, who has studied sweat. It&#39;s part of the reason a 75-degree day might feel toastier—and perhaps sweatier—in the spring than in the fall.<br><br> But we can&#39;t simply sweat our way out of our climatic bind. There&#39;s a <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.washingtonpost.com/weather/2023/07/18/extreme-heat-record-limits-human-survival/">ceiling to the temperatures we can tolerate</a> ; the body can leach only so much liquid out at once. Sweat&#39;s cooling power also tends to falter in humid conditions, when liquid can&#39;t evaporate as easily off of skin. Nor can researchers predict whether future generations might evolve to perspire much more than we do now. We no longer live under the intense conditions that pressured our ancestors to sprout more sweat glands—changes that also took place over many millions of years. It&#39;s even possible that we&#39;re fast approaching the maximal moistness a primate body can produce. “We don&#39;t have a great idea about the outer limits of that plasticity,” Jason Kamilar, a biological anthropologist at the University of Massachusetts at Amherst, told me.<br><br> For now, people who are already on the sweatier side may find themselves better equipped to deal with a warming world, Rittié told me. At long last: Blessed are the moist, for they shall inherit the Earth.<br><br></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Tue, 08 Aug 2023 14:04:03 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.theatlantic.com/health/archive/2023/08/sweat-perspiration-evolution-human-function/674951/</guid><link/> https://www.theatlantic.com/health/archive/2023/08/sweat-perspiration-evolution-human-function/674951/ </item><item><title><![CDATA[The Gender War Is Over in Britain]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div> While upholding trans rights, the Labour Party disassociates itself from radical postmodern theories. <br><figure><img src="https://cdn.theatlantic.com/thumbor/KyILJbm4emox0dXnrdzRLkVMDno=/0x0:2000x1125/960x540/media/img/mt/2023/08/labour_horz/original.jpg" alt="gender symbols interlaced to form a flower" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><figcaption> The Atlantic</figcaption></figure> <span class="smallcaps">When Keir Starmer</span> wanted to change the Labour Party&#39;s stance on sex and gender, he didn&#39;t give a set-piece speech or hold a press conference. Instead, the leader of Britain&#39;s main opposition party stayed in the background, leaving Anneliese Dodds, a shadow minister with a low public profile, to <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2023/jul/24/labour-will-lead-on-reform-of-transgender-rights-and-we-wont-take-lectures-from-the-divisive-tories">announce the shift</a> in a short opinion column in <em>The Guardian</em> . In just over 800 words, she made three big declarations. One was that “sex and gender are different.” Another was that, although Labour continues to believe in the right to change one&#39;s legal gender, safeguards are needed to “protect women and girls from predators who might abuse the system.” Finally, Labour was therefore dropping its commitment to self-ID—the idea that a simple online declaration is enough to change someone&#39;s legal gender for all purposes—and would retain the current requirement of a medical diagnosis of gender dysphoria.<br><br> Dodds supplemented her article with a few explanatory tweets, but didn&#39;t go on television to reiterate the message. The next day, Labour declined to provide a spokesperson for <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.google.com/url?q=https://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/m001p1nw&amp;sa=D&amp;source=docs&amp;ust=1691432639401313&amp;usg=AOvVaw1lDi1O5V-T3WeyCEmsH19B">comment</a> on the BBC&#39;s flagship radio news show. Although Starmer did eventually answer questions on the subject, as part of a wider <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.lbc.co.uk/news/keir-starmer-woman-adult-female-trans-labour-party/">interview</a> two days later, the overall effect was that of a man who had chucked a hand grenade over his shoulder and walked away, whistling.<br><br> To anyone not following the turbulent and sometimes arcane debate that has been raging in Britain, Dodds&#39;s statements might sound uncontroversial, but they are not. Since 2015, when the Conservative politician Maria Miller first proposed self-ID in Britain, the idea that such a system might be abused has been called a <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://slate.com/human-interest/2021/07/wi-spa-la-transphobic-protest.html">transphobic</a> <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2017/dec/15/trans-backlash-anti-gay-zealotry-section-28-homophobia">myth</a> by LGBTQ campaigners. Demands for single-sex sports teams, locker rooms, and prisons were thus “exclusionary” and analogous to whites-only buses, schools, and water fountains under <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://newhampshirebulletin.com/2022/05/06/transgender-athletes-and-a-national-history-of-exclusionary-practices-commentary/">apartheid</a> <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theguardian.com/sport/2023/jul/07/cisgender-female-athletes-solidarity-trans-athletes">and</a> <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.syracuse.com/us-news/2016/05/loretta_lynch_north_carolina_bathroom_law_jim_crow_laws.html">Jim Crow</a> . Labour, the main party of the British left, has now declared that these arguments are unfair and untrue. The <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.telegraph.co.uk/politics/2023/07/29/sir-keir-starmer-labour-trans-policy-duffield-russell-moyle/">internal</a> <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://twitter.com/LGBTLabour/status/1683390243733372929?s=20">dissent</a> has been notably muted.<br><br> <a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2023/02/nicola-sturgeon-resignation-scotland-transgender-bill/673067/">Helen Lewis: What happens when politicians brush off hard questions about gender</a><br><br> That shift has broader implications, not least in America, where combatants on both sides of the gender war closely follow the debates in Britain. (Queer activists in the US dismissively call the country “ <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.opendemocracy.net/en/5050/bbc-nolan-trans-lgbtiq/">TERF Island</a> .”) Labour&#39;s new stance shows how the left can simultaneously acknowledge the needs of an embattled transgender minority, accept the importance of biological sex to public policy, and look for political and social compromises. Admittedly, huge questions remain about how the party&#39;s proposals will work in practice and whether its Welsh and Scottish branches will fall in line. But Labour has signaled the beginning of a serious democratic conversation, after years of implicitly agreeing with the LGBTQ activists who insisted that <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://mermaidsuk.org.uk/news/trans-rights-are-not-up-for-debate/">no debate</a> was acceptable.<br><br> As a leader of a left-wing party, Starmer has sent an important sign by disassociating himself from the radical postmodern idea that the distinction between males and females is a <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.newstatesman.com/ideas/2023/07/the-gender-binary-debate-jacqueline-rose">social construct</a> , and that biology has nothing to do with women&#39;s historical oppression. (“Women are not, in fact, subordinated or oppressed by our bodies,” the feminist legal scholar Catharine MacKinnon wrote <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://signsjournal.org/exploring-transgender-law-and-politics/">recently</a> . “We do not need to be liberated from our chromosomes or our ovaries.”)<br><br> Labour&#39;s new position represents a big ideological shift, but it wasn&#39;t presented as one. That is typical of Starmer&#39;s personality, which is <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://helenlewis.substack.com/p/the-bluestocking-starmers-secret">unshowy but ruthless</a> . Unlike many American politicians on either side of the spectrum, he has tried to find a position that will make the debate less inflammatory, and to appeal to the wider country rather than his activist base.<br><br> In the three years since the Conservatives <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theguardian.com/society/2020/sep/22/uk-government-drops-gender-self-identification-plan-for-trans-people">dropped</a> their commitment to self-ID, some of their <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.mirror.co.uk/news/politics/tories-should-fight-next-election-29211636">politicians</a> have gleefully seized on the vote-winning potential of gender as a culture-war issue. By contrast, during that time, Starmer and his ministers have been fumbling over their answer to the question <em>What is a woman?</em> , talking about cervices far more than anyone outside a gynecology department would wish to. A desire to stick to the progressive line has meant that Labour politicians have ended up <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://uk.style.yahoo.com/labour-mp-dawn-butler-child-born-without-sex-150324736.html?guccounter=1&amp;guce_referrer=aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuZ29vZ2xlLmNvbS8&amp;guce_referrer_sig=AQAAAGjJ3Wh5kJtAmdZI9UFHqUUB-x9ZgHcLPdrmXEL5O7fSu8yyXfQDpt_cn4aWevKWa2Ze5NrVPslU2hnSIBC1AN7F1dFHE5DMRiuxxz1hOe7vgGlGePG7YJ0UFMrxnPe7JUWf6TTd98mXd-IpbBaK9FeGagNpbRvVQMbBgUk1AdyO">saying baffling things</a> like “A child is born without sex.” Some have attacked interviewers for even bringing up the subject, which just drew more attention to their tortured answers. Stuck arguing about the <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://news.sky.com/story/keir-starmer-says-99-9-of-women-havent-got-a-penis-as-he-faces-questions-over-trans-rights-12848438">exact percentage</a> of women who have a penis, Labour couldn&#39;t talk about Britain&#39;s housing crisis, high energy costs, crumbling infrastructure, poor economic growth, and high inflation.<br><br> That era is now over, if rank-and-file Labour politicians want it to be. Two days after the Dodds column appeared, Starmer <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.lbc.co.uk/news/keir-starmer-woman-adult-female-trans-labour-party/">was asked</a> to define <em>woman</em> . He responded simply, “An adult female.” If that answer is permissible in left-wing circles, interviewers have been deprived of an easy gotcha question, and Labour can go back to talking about economics and trying to win over the median voter.<br><br> <span class="smallcaps">For fear of</span> harming trans people or aligning with outright bigots, some on the left have avoided voicing misgivings about policies such as self-ID, and over the past decade Labour activists have <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://morningstaronline.co.uk/article/f/wpuk-fringe-report">vilified</a> <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/labour-officials-quit-in-transgender-row-06qtj2b3r">feminist commentators</a> who did speak up. Starmer has now broadened the limits of the discussion. Across Europe, medical associations are recommending <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2023/05/texas-puberty-blockers-gender-care-transgender-rights/673941/">caution</a> over so-called affirmative models of gender care for minors. The possibility that social contagion may affect teenagers&#39; professed identities is being <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.academie-medecine.fr/la-medecine-face-a-la-transidentite-de-genre-chez-les-enfants-et-les-adolescents/?lang=en">discussed</a> <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.bmj.com/content/376/bmj.o629/rr-1">among doctors</a> , as is the <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.bmj.com/company/newsroom/gender-dysphoria-in-young-people-is-rising-and-so-is-professional-disagreement/">suggestion</a> that, at least in some cases, puberty itself can resolve gender dysphoria. The lack of evidence for the safety or effectiveness of puberty blockers is <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.bmj.com/content/bmj/380/bmj.p697.full.pdf">becoming</a> <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.france24.com/en/live-news/20230208-sweden-puts-brakes-on-treatments-for-trans-minors">sayable</a> .<br><br> <a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2023/05/texas-puberty-blockers-gender-care-transgender-rights/673941/">Helen Lewis: The only way out of the child-gender culture war</a><br><br> In sports, international bodies are undoing previous policies that put trans women in competition with natal-female athletes. The latest organization to change its rules is <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.reuters.com/sports/british-rowing-ban-transgender-athletes-womens-events-telegraph-2023-08-02/">British Rowing</a> , which has restricted women&#39;s events to biological females, while also creating categories for transgender participation. Two weeks before that, cycling&#39;s world governing body, the Union Cycliste Internationale, <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.skysports.com/more-sports/other-sports/news/15264/12921233/uci-to-ban-transgender-women-from-participating-in-female-cycling-events-under-new-policy#:~:text=The%20policy%20created%20an%20'open,yet%20to%20begin%20hormone%20therapy.">restricted</a> the female category to individuals born female who have never taken testosterone, while also creating an “open” competition for anyone who has been through male puberty or has taken male hormones.<br><br> In the United States, though, political polarization is freezing a highly unproductive discussion in place. One of the most frustrating aspects of writing on this subject is that many liberals don&#39;t know what they don&#39;t know. Punitive red-state bans, coupled with <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2023/07/ron-desantis-cnn-interview/674751/">overtly anti-LGBTQ rhetoric</a> by Republicans, have made Democrats instinctively defensive of puberty blockers and gender surgery for minors even as European experts grow warier. A proper, evidence-based debate about child transition in America is inhibited by the fact that medical groups are wedded to the affirmative model, despite their overseas colleagues&#39; qualms about the evidence base. The board of the American Academy of Pediatrics just <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.nytimes.com/2023/08/03/health/aap-gender-affirming-care-evidence-review.html">voted unanimously</a> to continue backing the affirmative approach for now.<br><br> Clearly, a broad middle ground exists. About three-quarters of Americans are <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.washingtonpost.com/education/2023/05/05/trans-poll-gop-politics-laws/">opposed</a> to discrimination against transgender people in housing, colleges, the workplace, and obtaining health insurance, according to polling conducted late last year. But more than 60 percent of American adults also believe that trans women and girls should not compete in female sports at any level, and solid majorities also oppose hormone treatments for under-18s. Even among trans adults themselves, the same poll found that three in 10 support sex-based restrictions in sports, and the same number said it was inappropriate for younger children to receive puberty blockers. ( <em>The</em> <em>Washington Post</em> , which published the polling, notes that it was conducted before the introduction of hundreds of red-state bills restricting medical care and sports participation.) It seems as though most Americans are happy to support trans people in everyday life, while also believing that trans women are not identical to other women, with all that implies. But this position is rarely articulated among elites on either side. “It&#39;s not just tribalism; it&#39;s extremism,” the writer Lisa Selin Davis told me. “It&#39;s the two-party system, and it&#39;s each party catering to its most radical constituents. And of course, that&#39;s the story of social media too.”<br><br> Davis came to the American gender debate as the parent of a masculine daughter. When she wrote about that experience in <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.nytimes.com/2017/04/18/opinion/my-daughter-is-not-transgender-shes-a-tomboy.html"><em>The New York Times</em></a> , she received letters urging her to let her “son” transition and warning that “he” might die by suicide otherwise. She still considers herself to be on the left but believes that her natural allies have lost perspective. “When it comes to the Democrats, they have invested so much political capital in supporting things that not only probably don&#39;t matter to most Democratic voters, but I think probably are a bit of a turnoff,” she told me. “Staking your claim on supporting drag-queen story hour, as opposed to a $25 minimum wage, is really silly.”<br><br> Davis is particularly dispirited that Democrats do not make life easy for lawmakers who depart from the party&#39;s orthodoxy on gender issues. Shawn Thierry, a Black female Democratic state representative in Texas, faced censure motions and a primary challenge after <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.houstonchronicle.com/politics/texas/article/houston-democrat-transgender-care-ban-18100564.php">supporting</a> a Republican bill to limit gender-related hormone therapies to people over 18. Her Democratic colleagues accused her of parroting GOP talking points, but she insisted that she had looked at the evidence and found it wanting. Her detractors were also unhappy that she met with two detransitioners ahead of the vote. Imagine that—a lawmaker being criticized for listening to people with personal experience of the issue under discussion.<br><br> <a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2023/01/detransition-transgender-nonbinary-gender-affirming-care/672745/">Daniela Valdes and Kinnon MacKinnon: Take detransitioners seriously</a><br><br> Deviations from the Republican Party line also attract ferocious pushback. In 2021, Asa Hutchinson, then the governor of Arkansas, vetoed a child-gender-care bill, drawing criticism from <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.nbcnews.com/meet-the-press/meetthepressblog/tucker-carlson-asa-hutchinson-tussle-transgender-rights-vaccines-rcna94305">Tucker Carlson</a> and the state party. But Hutchinson gave a compelling rationale: He opposed surgeries on minors but felt the bill was unconstitutional and deprived parents of their rights. (His veto was overturned, but the law has since been <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://abcnews.go.com/US/judge-strikes-gender-affirming-care-ban-arkansas/story?id=100257964">struck down</a> by a judge.) Earlier this year, Utah Governor Spencer Cox <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://news.yahoo.com/disagree-better-utah-governor-wants-143000349.html">approved</a> restrictions on transition care in his state only <em>after</em> meeting with families affected by the change, telling reporters: “If you&#39;re not willing to sit down and listen to transgender kids and their families, then you&#39;re probably doing policy the wrong way.” Cox is now using his year as chair of the National Governors Association to promote an initiative called Disagree Better.<br><br> Here in Britain, Starmer is betting that most voters will gratefully accept his proposed compromise—one that both assuages their concerns and takes some of the heat out of the debate. Labour has made concessions to trans activists, too, by proposing a system that will allow patients to receive a dysphoria diagnosis from their family doctor, rather than having to apply to an anonymous panel. Starmer has so far declined <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2023/07/25/keir-starmer-owes-rosie-duffield-an-apology/">to apologize</a> on the party&#39;s behalf to feminists who were harassed for views that Labour now officially shares.<br><br> Frankly, treating this as a tough but mundane problem to be solved rather than an emotive means of attacking the opposition is what is needed. It&#39;s the only way to make the American conversation around gender more like the British one. Democrats need to meet detransitioners, and Republicans need to meet transgender activists. Both sides need to hear the best version of their opponents&#39; arguments—and ensure that the debate is being conducted on the basis of the best available evidence. Alongside any evidence reviews, Davis wants a bipartisan commission on child gender care. “The best thing to do would be to stop fighting and get the data,” she said.<br><br> Until then, the left must be able to defend trans rights without denying the meaningful differences between males and females. The right must be able to air concerns without demonizing trans people. Both liberals and conservatives should stop throwing around accusations of child abuse toward parents doing their best. The gender war can end—if the broad, tolerant middle asserts itself.<br><br></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Tue, 08 Aug 2023 11:30:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2023/08/uk-trans-rights-labour-party/674944/</guid><link/> https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2023/08/uk-trans-rights-labour-party/674944/ </item><item><title><![CDATA[The Local-News Crisis Is Weirdly Easy to Solve]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div> Restoring the journalism jobs lost over the past 20 years wouldn&#39;t just be cheap—it would pay for itself. <br><figure><img src="https://cdn.theatlantic.com/thumbor/OxjtWxqBQ3MegS-BPLwSTdRukEI=/0x0:2000x1125/960x540/media/img/mt/2023/08/local_news_final_horz/original.jpg" alt="a newspaper-dispenser box full of money" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><figcaption> Illustration by Ben Kothe / The Atlantic. Source: Getty.</figcaption></figure> Z <span class="smallcaps">ak Podmore</span> did not bring down a corrupt mayor. He did not discover secret torture sites or expose abuses by a powerful religious institution. But there was something about this one article he wrote as a reporter for <i>The Salt Lake Tribune</i> in 2019 that changed my conception of the value of local news.<br><br> Podmore, then a staff journalist for the <i>Tribune</i> and a corps member of Report for America, a nonprofit I co-founded, published a story <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.sltrib.com/news/2019/07/28/san-juan-county-paid/">revealing</a> that San Juan County, Utah, had paid a single law firm hundreds of thousands of dollars in lobbying fees. Among other things, Podmore found that the firm had overcharged the county, the poorest in the state, by $109,500. Spurred by his story, the firm paid the money back. Perhaps because it didn&#39;t involve billions of dollars, but rather a more imaginable number, it struck me: In one story, Podmore had retrieved for the county a sum that was triple his annual salary.<br><br> <a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/magazine/archive/2021/11/alden-global-capital-killing-americas-newspapers/620171/">From the November 2021 Issue: A secretive hedge fund is gutting newsrooms</a><br><br> You&#39;ve probably read about the collapse of local news over the past two decades. On average, two newspapers <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://localnewsinitiative.northwestern.edu/research/state-of-local-news/report/">close</a> each week. Some 1,800 communities that used to have local news now <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.usnewsdeserts.com/reports/news-deserts-and-ghost-newspapers-will-local-news-survive/the-news-landscape-in-2020-transformed-and-diminished/">don&#39;t</a> . Many of the papers still hanging on are forced to make do with skeleton staffs as their owners, often private-equity firms, seek to cut costs. The number of newspaper newsroom employees dropped by 57 percent from 2008 to 2020, according to a <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.pewresearch.org/short-reads/2021/07/13/u-s-newsroom-employment-has-fallen-26-since-2008/">Pew Research study</a> , leading to thousands of “ghost newspapers” that barely cover their community.<br><br> For the past 15 years, I have been part of an effort to reverse this trend. That means I&#39;ve grown used to talking about the threat that news deserts pose to American democracy. After all, the whole concept of democratic self-government depends on the people knowing what public officials are up to. That&#39;s impossible without a watchdog press. Researchers have linked the decline of local news to decreased voter participation and higher rates of corruption, along with increased polarization and more ideologically extreme elected officials. At this point, I can make high-minded speeches about this stuff in my sleep, with Thomas Jefferson quotes and everything. Recently, however, I&#39;ve come to realize that I have been ignoring a less lofty but perhaps more persuasive argument: Funding local news would more than pay for itself.<br><br> Unlike other seemingly intractable problems, the demise of local news wouldn&#39;t cost very much money to reverse. Journalists are not particularly well compensated. Assuming an average salary of $60,000 (generous by industry standards), it would cost only about $1.5 billion a year to sustain 25,000 local-reporter positions, a rough estimate of the number that have disappeared nationwide over the past two decades. That&#39;s two-hundredths of a percent of federal spending in 2022. I personally think this would be an amount well worth sacrificing to save American democracy. But the amazing thing is that it wouldn&#39;t really be a sacrifice at all. If more public or philanthropic money were directed toward sustaining local news, it would most likely produce financial benefits many times greater than the cost.<br><br> What do government officials do when no one&#39;s watching? Often, they enrich themselves or their allies at the taxpayers&#39; expense. In the 2000s, some years after its local paper shut down, the city of Bell, California, a low-income, overwhelmingly Latino community, raised the pay of the city manager to $787,637 and that of the police chief to $457,000. The <i>Los Angeles Times</i> eventually <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.latimes.com/local/la-me-bell-salary-20100715-story.html">exposed</a> the graft, and several city officials ended up in prison. Prosecutors accused them of costing taxpayers at least $5.5 million through their inflated salaries. These salaries were approved at municipal meetings, which is to say that if even one reporter (say, with a salary of $60,000) had been in attendance, the city might have saved millions of dollars.<br><br> Sometimes the work of journalists prompts government investigations into the private sector, which, in turn, produce fines that go into the public&#39;s bank account. After the <i>Tampa Bay Times</i> <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.tampabay.com/investigations/2022/05/09/tampa-bay-times-reporters-win-pulitzer-prize-for-poisoned-series/">found</a> that a battery recycler was exposing its employees and the surrounding community to high levels of lead and other toxins, regulators fined the company $800,000. A ProPublica <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.propublica.org/article/sec-issues-more-fines-over-magnetar-deals-and-appears-to-move-on">investigation</a> into one firm&#39;s questionable mortgage-backed securities prompted investigations by the Security and Exchange Commission, which ultimately assessed $435 million in fines. A review of more than 12,000 entries in the Investigative Reporters and Editors Awards found that about one in 10 triggered fines from the government, and twice as many prompted audits.<br><br> In other cases, local-news organizations return money directly to consumers by forcing better behavior from private institutions. MLK50, a local newsroom in Memphis, <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.propublica.org/article/what-happens-after-a-debt-collection-machine-grinds-to-a-halt">teamed up</a> with ProPublica to report that Methodist Le Bonheur Healthcare had sued more than 8,300 people, many of them poor, for unpaid hospital bills. In response, the faith-based institution erased nearly $12 million in debt.<br><br> Of course, most journalism does not convert quite so immediately into cash on hand. The impacts may be enormous but indirect. One study of toxic emissions at 40,000 plants <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/abs/pii/S0095069616301371">found</a> that when newspapers reported on pollution, emissions declined by 29 percent compared with plants that were not covered. The study did not track the ripple effects, but it stands to reason that residents in the less polluted areas would have fewer health problems, which in turn would translate to lower medical costs and less lost work time. Another <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://papers.ssrn.com/sol3/papers.cfm?abstract_id=3175555">study</a> , by the scholars Pengjie Gao, Chang Lee, and Dermot Murphy, looked at bond offerings in communities with and without local news from 1996 to 2015. It concluded that for each bond offering, the borrowing costs were five to 11 basis points higher in the less covered communities. That translated to additional costs of $650,000 an issue, on average.<br><br> <a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2021/05/local-news-media-trust-americans/618895/">Amanda Ripley: Can the news be fixed?</a><br><br> One academic tried to track the economic effects even further downstream. In his book <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://tertulia.com/book/democracy-s-detectives-the-economics-of-investigative-journalism-james-t-hamilton/9780674545502?affiliate_id=atl-347"><i>Democracy&#39;s Detectives: The Economics of Investigative Journalism</i></a> ,<i> </i>the Stanford professor James Hamilton looked at a series by KCBS in Los Angeles that uncovered a flawed restaurant-inspection program. The exposé prompted LA County to require restaurants to display their inspection scores, which in turn led to a 13.3 percent drop in LA County hospital admissions for food poisoning. Hamilton estimated a savings of about $148,000. In another case study, Hamilton analyzed a series by the Raleigh <i>News &amp; Observer</i> that found that, because the state criminal-justice system didn&#39;t adequately keep track of those under supervision, 580 people on probation in North Carolina killed someone from 2000 to 2008. After the state implemented reforms, murders committed by people on probation declined. Applying the statistical “value of human life” used by the US Department of Transportation, Hamilton concluded that society saved about $62 million in just the first year after the policy changes. The series cost only about $200,000 to produce.<br><br> Ideally, investment in local news would come from the federal government, which has more freedom to think long-term than cash-strapped states and municipalities do. <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.rebuildlocalnews.org/">The Rebuild Local News coalition</a> , of which I am president, supports legislation that would provide a refundable tax credit for news organizations that employ local reporters, and a tax break for small businesses that advertise in local news. A <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.rebuildlocalnews.org/community-news-small-business-support-act/">new version</a> of the bill was just introduced in the House of Representatives by the Republican Claudia Tenney and the Democrat Suzan DelBene. Civic-minded philanthropists focused on high-impact donations should also put money into local news, given the likely societal returns. It&#39;s impossible to quantify exactly how much money would be generated for government and consumers by restoring the health of local news. But it&#39;s nearly as hard to deny that the investment would pay off handsomely. And the saving-democracy part? Well, that&#39;s just gravy.<br><br></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Tue, 08 Aug 2023 11:30:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2023/08/local-news-investment-economic-value/674942/</guid><link/> https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2023/08/local-news-investment-economic-value/674942/ </item><item><title><![CDATA[Trees? Not in My Backyard.]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>一个关于三棵树、愤怒的“社区”和华盛顿特区权力的故事<br><figure><img src="https://cdn.theatlantic.com/thumbor/C3iRoI6hkPEQlcPImgJS1xlo8hU=/0x0:4800x2700/960x540/media/img/mt/2023/08/xenia_trees_2/original.jpg" alt="树根，上面画着地图和红点" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><figcaption>乔安妮·因佩里奥/《大西洋月刊》插图。资料来源：盖蒂；国会图书馆。</figcaption></figure> “I <span class="smallcaps">t&#39;s almost like</span> the government&#39;s imposing its will on its residents,” Trayon White, the DC council member for Ward 8, said at the council&#39;s June 6 legislative meeting.他说的不是拟议中的高速公路、地铁站、发电厂，或者——<em>打消这个想法</em>——公寓楼。他谈论的是树木：具体来说，是几年前华盛顿特区城市林业部门在 Xenia 街上种植的三棵椴树。令我惊讶的是，美国一个主要城市的立法机构正在经历<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.washingtonpost.com/dc-md-va/2023/05/05/dc-homeless-annual-count/">无家可归者</a>不断升级和暴力<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://mpdc.dc.gov/page/district-crime-data-glance">犯罪</a>严重激增的情况，那天专门用了四分之一的时间来讨论三棵树。<br><br>怀特表示，他担心房地产价值的潜在风险，以及他认为“合理的担忧”，即一旦成熟，这些树木将“大到足以让人难以看清人行道及其周围的情况，这是一条公共道路”。安全问题。”他要求他的同事支持一项紧急决议，以便在这种情况发生之前将其移除。<br><br>有一段时间，成员们继续说，好像这对他们来说是一件完全正常的事情。一些人认为扩大树冠也许实际上是件好事。但没有人真正质疑怀特提议的基本前提：社区已经起来反对树木恐惧症。<br><br> <a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/magazine/archive/2021/07/social-trees-meg-lowman-suzanne-simard/619015/">摘自 2021 年 7 月/8 月号：观察树木的更好方法</a><br><br>怀特说：“我们要指出的是，这些房主担心自己的房屋价值。” “我只是相信 [地区交通部 (DDOT)] 可以更友好地响应社区的需求，提出他们的要求，如果他们要求不同的树木，我不明白有什么大问题”。<br><br>委员会继续讨论公共安全问题的优点。议员肯尼·麦克杜菲回忆说，在他的选区内，市政府在停车位上种植了树木，以免侵占本已狭窄的人行道。 “我仍然质疑受影响社区是否有适当程度的协商和参与，”他表示支持怀特。<br><br> 20多分钟后，理事会主席惊讶地指出，“我们在移除三棵树的问题上花了这么多时间。”怀特认识到同事们缺乏足够的支持，因此将此事从议程中撤回，让树木再生长一天。<br><br>最初吸引我看到这个故事的是理事会会议上的言论与当前的主题之间明显不匹配。几棵树怎么会对公共安全或财产价值构成威胁？这些树是不是特别丑？<em>谁</em>是怀特推动将其移除的幕后黑手？就像许多关于政府的故事一样，这部看似微不足道的戏剧其实是关于权力，以及人们如何证明使用权力的合理性。<br><br> Xenia<span class="smallcaps">街</span>位于第 8 区，与华盛顿特区的大部分地区仅隔阿纳科斯蒂亚河 (Anacostia River)。这并不是它与众不同的唯一原因。 This side of the river is <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://censusreporter.org/profiles/61000US11008-ward-8-dc/">overwhelmingly Black</a> and has a higher unemployment rate, a lower labor-force-participation rate, and a higher poverty rate than the rest of the city. The census tract that contains Xenia Street is one of the most heat sensitive in the city, a metric that reflects the prevalence of asthma, coronary heart disease, and disability, as well as racial demographics and income.华盛顿特区城市林业部（DDOT 的一个部门）在<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.aphis.usda.gov/aphis/resources/pests-diseases/hungry-pests/the-threat/emerald-ash-borer/emerald-ash-borer-beetle#:~:text=The%20Emerald%20Ash%20Borer%20(Agrilus,hidden%20in%20wood%20packing%20materials.">甲虫侵扰</a>损害了当地几棵白蜡树后种植了这些树木。一位高级官员告诉我，该部门普遍担心各区树冠分布不均：截至 6 月底，第 8 区收到了大约 500 个新种植的公开请求；收入较高的第四区有近 6,000 人。<br><br>植树不符合新道路或火车站可能需要的更严格类型的通知和社区输入流程的标准。 But according to Kay Armstead, a former member of the Advisory Neighborhood Commission—an elected body meant to serve as a hyperlocal voice on zoning, bike lanes, liquor licenses—the city did inform the commission of a plan to bring more trees to the neighborhood. 2020 年秋季，该公司在两栋公寓楼（450 Xenia Street 和 450 Condon Terrace）之间的公共土地上种植了 35 棵树，其中一些是美国椴树，一些是苹果。<br><br>我想亲眼看看这些树。在怀特提出紧急决议后的几周内，我在三个不同的场合参观了这条安静的住宅街道，询问人们是否对这些树有任何想法。我采访过的人都没有表达强烈的意见，甚至没有听说过这场争议。<br><br> 450 Condon Terrace 的一位居民立即将我的注意力转移到她停车场地面上的一个大洞上，她说这是由一辆垃圾车造成的。另一位告诉我，他没有听说过这场争议，但想谈谈垃圾收集问题。 “我的意思是，看看这狗屎，”他指着人行道上的一堆垃圾说道。树？在优先事项列表中排名靠后。至少可以说，另一个人发现我的提问令人困惑。 “它们是氧气！”当我说有些人担心这些树会鼓励犯罪时，他嘲笑我。 “现在，你知道这太疯狂了。谁会躲在这些树下？”<br><br> <a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2019/10/big-little-ideas-start-planting-trees/622142/">詹姆斯·法洛斯：开始植树</a><br><br>那么是谁组成了如此反对树木的“社区”呢？他的名字叫达里尔·罗斯。<br><br>几十年来，罗斯一直活跃于地方政治。他是第八选区民主党和怀特<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.washingtonpost.com/local/dc-politics/just-a-quarter-of-dc-constituent-service-funds-provided-assistance-report-finds/2019/03/26/191d0f80-4fc8-11e9-88a1-ed346f0ec94f_story.html">选民服务基金</a>的财务主管，该基金是一个备受争议的钱包，一些批评者称其为“行贿基金”。当怀特提到选民就这个问题向他的办公室进行外展时，他指的是罗斯。 （怀特和他的幕僚长都拒绝接受本文的采访。）罗斯不住在 450 Xenia Street，但他以前住在 450 Xenia Street。他仍然拥有该大楼的一个单位，并将其出租，并且是 Xenia 公寓业主协会的主席。<br><br>从这些树被种植的那天起，罗斯就对它们感到愤怒。 He told me he saw workers digging and began calling around, furious that no one had informed the neighborhood about the project, astounded that the city thought 35 trees (“a forest!”) made sense on the street, and frustrated by hypothetical future private costs that the trees would impose on residents.<br><br>他提出的移除树木的 311 请求毫无结果。因此，他尝试了DDOT和城市林业部的官员、怀特和市议会的其他几位成员、监察长办公室以及邻里咨询委员会的现任和前任成员。他知道，如果没有人脉关系，他不可能获得如此多的关注：“相信我，我正在利用一切可能的手段来获得想要的结果，”他告诉我。<br><br> After months of effort, in August of 2021, representatives from DDOT, White&#39;s chief of staff, and a senior staffer for at-large Council Member Anita Bonds met with Ross and a couple of area residents on the site to discuss the problem.官员们同意移除 35 棵新种植的树木中的 14 棵。该机构还承诺完成照明调查，安装了三盏大型路灯，这是一种<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://urbanlabs.uchicago.edu/projects/crime-lights-study">减少犯罪的数据驱动方法</a>。<br><br> The “desire to compromise for this individual is because we want to make sure we&#39;re doing this <em>for</em> people, not <em>to</em> them,” a senior official in the Urban Forestry department (who requested anonymity to speak freely) told me. “如果我们能够安抚某人，产生一种主人翁意识……你就可以让某人成为你的盟友。”<br><br>罗斯并没有平静下来。他继续努力，又砍掉了三棵树——最靠近他的公寓大楼人行道的树。他向华盛顿特区监察长办公室提出投诉，DDOT 局长埃弗雷特·洛特 (Everett Lott) 做出了正式回应，他辩称，该部门在种植树木方面没有违反法律，实际上超出了公众通报的授权。罗斯没有被吓倒，继续他的倡导，最终怀特在六月的市议会会议上提出了紧急决议。<br><br>罗斯让我与他的一些盟友取得了联系，其中大多数人听起来只比我在访问中随机遇到的居民更了解情况。有些人不知道许多树木已经被砍伐；其他人只是模糊地意识到，在某一时刻，树木似乎是一个问题。一位女士告诉我，她认为孩子们可能会将掉落的苹果扔到汽车或建筑物窗户上。 （紧急立法中涉及的树木是椴树，而不是苹果。）<br><br>罗斯表示，公寓协会团结一致反对。他在我在场的情况下通过扬声器给副总统哈泽尔·法默打电话。<br><br> “你还记得有四棵[树]离人行道太近了吗？”他问。<br><br> “我以为我们已经完成了，”她说道，听起来很困惑。<br><br> “不不，我们还在战斗。”罗斯连忙回答道。<br><br>罗斯恢复记忆后，法默说，她担心有一天这些树会推高混凝土人行道，阻碍居民进出大楼。罗斯后来澄清说，法默已经搬出去了，因为人行道上的台阶对她来说太困难了。<br><br> I <span class="smallcaps">na July legislative meeting,</span> White withdrew the emergency resolution, citing a compromise reached by the chair of the DC council and DDOT to apply a growth regulator to the offending saplings.这一结果激怒了罗斯，他正在寻求与市长穆里尔·鲍泽会面：“最终我们投票给了她，我们没有投票给[DDOT官员]，我们相信她会做对社会最有利的事情。”人们。”<br><br>罗斯仍然有选择。如果最坏的情况发生，这些树最终延伸到人行道上，他可以拨打 311 请求修剪树木。据市林业局称，这些请求平均会在 20 天内得到解决。<br><br> But the more I talked with Ross and his allies, the more I realized that the trees were also stand-ins for their broader unhappiness with DDOT, which they see as not acting <em>for</em> them but doing things <em>to</em> them: bike racks “just dropped” in front of some businesses, bike lanes constructed over their objections, and traffic-safety infrastructure— <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.arcgis.com/apps/dashboards/a2f1cca5159e4c6eae197895d2e08336">in DC&#39;s highest traffic-fatality ward</a> —installed without their consent. This is why Ross was able to enlist supporters in the first place—by tapping into existing anger some residents feel toward the city&#39;s transportation agency.愤怒的是，在近9万人的病房里，少数人没有说了算。<br><br>这是地方政府及其不满的经典故事。政府采取行动。愤怒的、人脉广泛的当地人士进行了反击，对没有征求他们的意见而感到恼火。但当他们反击并声称符合“人民”的意愿时，我们如何知道他们是否正确？稍微备份一下：我们如何决定这些<em>人是谁</em>？<br><br> <a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/magazine/archive/2023/07/local-government-power-nimby-denver/674164/">From the July/August 2023 issue: Colorado&#39;s ingenious idea for solving the housing crisis</a><br><br>在《仙妮亚街》剧集中，是住在树旁边的人们吗？隔一条街怎么样？只是像罗斯这样的业主吗？因为树木位于公共土地上，所以所有特区居民都应该有发言权吗？都是美国人吗？解决<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.usda.gov/media/press-releases/2022/07/25/biden-harris-administration-announces-plans-reforestation-climate#:~:text=WASHINGTON%2C%20July%2025%2C%202022%20%E2%80%94,trees%20over%20the%20next%20decade.">重新造林积压问题是国家的首要任务</a>。或者，考虑到树木有助于缓解气候变化，<em>所有人都</em>应该有发言权吗？这就是所谓的边界问题，政治学家罗伯特·达尔曾调侃说，这个问题“没有理论解决方案”，只有务实的解决方案。即使调查全人类在理论上是可取的，但实际上也是不可能的。人们必须在某处划定界限并委派代表或发言人。<br><br>可以说，在这个问题上最好的代表是地方民选官员，他们从选民那里获得权力。问题在于，在地方层面，尤其是超地方层面，没有人投票。 In 2018, <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.washingtonblade.com/2018/08/17/two-thirds-of-d-c-neighborhood-races-uncontested/">two-thirds of Advisory Neighborhood Commission races were uncontested</a> .即使这些竞赛竞争激烈，也只有少数人出席投票。在包括森尼亚街在内的单一议员选区，罗斯的盟友之一阿姆斯特德以<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://electionresults.dcboe.org/election_results/2022-General-Election">137-91</a>落败。去年， <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://dcist.com/story/22/12/01/two-dc-races-to-be-decided-by-casting-of-lots/">选举日后，非国大两场比赛打成平手</a>。在其中一项选举中，每位候选人均获得了 12 票，而在另一项选举中，每位候选人只获得了一张选票（大概是他们自己的）。确实是大众之声。<br><br> If the ANC can&#39;t quite speak for the people, what about the DC council, and specifically Council Member White?市议会的投票率也很低： <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://data.census.gov/table?q=B29001:+CITIZEN,+VOTING-AGE+POPULATION+BY+AGE&amp;g=040XX00US11%246100000_1400000US11001000101&amp;tid=ACSDT5Y2021.B29001">在第 8 选区约 57,000 名达到投票年龄的公民</a>中，约有 8,700 人在确保怀特连任的 2020 年初选中投票。<br><br> DDOT 怎么样？作为行政部门的一个机构，DDOT 的权力来自市长。 2022 年，鲍泽市长在初选（这座民主党占主导地位的城市的真正选举）期间从第 8 选区获得了不到 4,000 张选票。 Only about 10,000 people in the ward voted at all in that contest.<br><br>民选官员在民主上合法化并不存在什么神奇的门槛。但超过一半的合格选民<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.census.gov/newsroom/press-releases/2023/2022-voting-registration.html#:~:text=Turnout%20rates%20for%20the%20citizen,%25)%20citizen%20voting%2Dage%20population.">通常都会参加</a>联邦和州的竞选，而我们的市政选举<a data-event-element="inline link" href="http://www.whovotesformayor.org/">却很难争取到 15% 的选票</a>。我们在地方政府中看到的是其他级别政府无与伦比的民主危机。<br><br> “我<span class="smallcaps">不是树木，而是树木。”</span>这是不尊重，”阿姆斯特德告诉我。她称砍伐树木是首要任务，因为“当你来到一个社区而不倾听时，[我们]就会受到不尊重和忽视。”罗斯也提出了类似的观点：“这让我很生气，因为就像我说的，我们是利益相关者。我们是纳税人。我们为华盛顿特区政府雇员、议会提供工资......这是我们的钱！”<br><br>当我们集体认为有权让政府承担责任时，那就是民主。但当个人这样做时，那就是另一回事了：制度俘获。<br><br>由于很少有人在地方选举中投票，那些敢于发声并声称代表社区发言的人的力量很难受到挑战。如果以邻里爱管闲事的人为首的房主协会说他代表你说话，你会出现对这种说法提出异议吗？罗斯的毅力显而易见，其有效性很大程度上归功于其独特性。 If <em>everyone</em> engaged as he did—called and emailed and attended meeting after meeting, filed complaints with everyone from the office of the inspector general on down—his power would dilute instantly.如果每个人都为自己说话，那么没有人可以声称代表社区说话。<br><br>民主是关于反馈循环的。我们选举人。如果他们做得不好，我们就会选择替代方案。但当选举制度因废弃而动摇时，其他反馈循环就会生根发芽。地方一级的民选官员要对极少数参与其中但不具代表性的选民负责；公务员对人脉广泛的人变得先发敏感，因为他们有时间和精力要求过度关注。<br><br>像罗斯这样的人可能无法得到他们想要的一切，但他们知道如何吸引注意力。 No fewer than four DC council members have become personally involved in the matter of the trees on Xenia Street.与此同时，地面上那个巨大的洞？它还在那里。<br><br></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Tue, 08 Aug 2023 11:00:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2023/08/trees-xenia-street-washington-dc-local-government/674949/</guid><link/> https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2023/08/trees-xenia-street-washington-dc-local-government/674949/ </item><item><title><![CDATA[Killer Apps]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>社交媒体是否让美国的谋杀案激增变得更糟？ <br><figure><img src="https://cdn.theatlantic.com/thumbor/BsZBNpGQ7buWlTQSboDFdaRRL8Q=/258x0:1259x1251/648x810/media/img/2023/08/01/DIS_McGillis_InstaViolence/original.jpg" alt="一只手指着一把枪口形状像 Instagram 标志的枪" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><figcaption>埃里克·卡特插图</figcaption></figure><small><i data-stringify-type="italic">This article was featured in One Story to Read Today, a newsletter in which our editors recommend a single must-read from</i> The Atlantic <i data-stringify-type="italic">, Monday through Friday.</i> <i data-stringify-type="italic"><a data-event-element="inline link" data-sk="tooltip_parent" data-stringify-link="https://www.theatlantic.com/newsletters/sign-up/one-story-to-read-today/" delay="150" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/newsletters/sign-up/one-story-to-read-today/" rel="noopener noreferrer" target="_blank">Sign up for it here.</a></i></small><br><br> <span class="smallcaps">2020 年的一个秋天晚上</span>，贾雷尔·杰克逊 (Jarell Jackson) 和沙贾汉·麦卡斯基尔 (Shahjahan McCaskill) 正在杰克逊的现代索纳塔 (Hyundai Sonata) 中聊天， <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.inquirer.com/news/west-philadelphia-shootings-homicide-rates-instagram-feuds-20210316.html">当时还处于假期后的兴奋状态，突然 24 颗子弹射穿了汽车</a>。这两个人都是 26 岁，从学前班起就是亲密的朋友。他们在波多黎各玩了几天悬挂式滑翔、滑索和徒步旅行后刚刚返回西费城。杰克逊把车停在他妈妈的房子外面，这时一辆黑色SUV停了下来，车内的人开始开枪。他和麦卡斯基尔均在医院被宣布死亡。<br><br>事后，麦卡斯基尔的母亲纳吉拉·扎伊纳布·阿里·麦卡斯基尔无法理解为什么有人想要杀死她的儿子和他的朋友。两人都战胜了附近年轻黑人的困境，并从大学毕业。杰克逊曾是青少年精神病房的心理健康技术员，而她的儿子则经营一家小型清洁公司并经营酒吧。她想知道他们是否是一名心怀不满的清洁公司前雇员的目标。但随后警方解释说：她的儿子和他的朋友因社交媒体上一些从未谋面的青少年之间发生冲突而被杀。<br><br>几个月来，市场街两边的工作人员在 Instagram 上展开了一场激烈的战斗。他们之间的竞争由来已久，但网上一连串的嘲讽和威胁加剧了社区的紧张气氛。警方已指派一名警官监视该市各个人员的社交媒体活动，该部门怀疑SUV中的北边人将这两个朋友中的一个误认为是竞争对手南边人并开枪。枪击事件发生一小时后，一名北区人在 Instagram 上发布了一张照片，其标题似乎是在嘲笑受害者，并鼓励对手的工作人员来收集他们的尸体：“啊哈啊，猫把他们捡起来！！”<br><br>杰克逊和麦卡斯基尔在全国暴力活动死灰复燃的第一年去世，这场暴力活动抹去了二十多年来公共安全方面取得的成果。 2020 年，凶杀案激增 30%，并在接下来的两年里围绕该水平波动。有<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2023/06/us-murder-rate-decline-crime-statistics/674290/">初步迹象</a>表明，2023 年的比率可能会比去年下降 10% 以上，但这仍将远高于大流行前的水平。<br><br>犯罪学家指出了多种因素的综合作用，包括 COVID-19 造成的社会混乱、大流行初期枪支销售的增加，以及乔治·弗洛伊德被谋杀后的骚动，这在许多城市导致警察活动减少和对警察的信任进一步受到侵蚀。但在我对这一激增的报道中，我不断听到另一个促进因素：社交媒体。<br><br>暴力预防工作人员描述了从 Instagram、Snapchat 和其他平台开始的争斗，并以惊人的速度爆发到现实生活中。 “当我年轻的时候，我会在学校与某人发生争执，唯一知道这件事的人就是我和学校里的人，”巴尔的摩的暴力预防工作者詹姆斯·廷普森说。 “不是现在。在你离开学校之前，就有五百人知道了。然后一场大战就开始了。”<br><br> <a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/newsletters/archive/2022/04/american-teens-sadness-depression-anxiety/629524/">阅读：为什么美国青少年如此悲伤</a><br><br>智能手机和社交平台早在凶杀案激增之前就已存在。它们显然不是其唯一原因。但考虑到最近的过去，就不难看出为什么社交媒体可能成为新的暴力暴力驱动因素。当疫情导致官员关闭学校、图书馆和娱乐中心等市政中心一年多时，人们——尤其是年轻人——被进一步推入虚拟空间。关于大量使用社交媒体与青少年心理健康问题和自杀之间可能存在的联系，人们已经讨论了很多。现在，廷普森和其他暴力预防工作者正在将这种担忧带入合乎逻辑的下一步。如果社交媒体在年轻人伤害自己的倾向上升中发挥了作用，那么当他们伤害他人时，它是否也会发挥作用呢？<br><br>目前暴力事件的激增并不是谋杀率回到了 90 年代，而是完全不同的情况。在许多城市，暴力尤其集中在年轻人中。从 2014 年到 2021 年，全国 15 至 19 岁青少年的凶杀率 <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.cdc.gov/nchs/products/databriefs/db471.htm">惊人地增加了 91%。</a>去年，华盛顿特区<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.washingtonpost.com/dc-md-va/2022/12/31/homicides-dc-va-md-2022/">有 105 名 18 岁以下青少年被枪杀</a>，几乎是前一年的两倍。 2022 年前 9 个月，费城青少年枪击受害者人数为 181 人<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.axios.com/local/philadelphia/2022/10/05/philadelphia-gun-violence-youth-victims">，相当于 2015 年和 2016 年全年的总人数</a>。在巴尔的摩，今年上半年已有 60 多名 13 至 18 岁的儿童遭到枪杀。这是<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.thebaltimorebanner.com/community/criminal-justice/teen-shootings-gun-violence-baltimore-UW47CTUZVVFCZDMHUVZOY3WGJQ/">2015 年至 2021 年上半年凶杀案总数的两倍</a>，而且发生在该市凶杀案总体下降的时期。在全国范围内，这种趋势在种族上已经达到了极端程度：2021年，10岁至24岁的黑人<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://stacks.cdc.gov/view/cdc/121555">成为凶杀案受害者的可能性几乎是年轻白人的14倍</a>。<br><br>那些面对这一祸害的人——警察、检察官、干预人员——坚信社交媒体的煽动有助于解释为什么今天的年轻人在受害者中所占比例更大。但他们不知道如何应对这种现象。他们明白这波新的杀戮浪潮需要新的解决方案——但它们是什么？<br><br><span class="smallcaps">就网络煽动引起关注的程度而言</span>，它主要集中在说唱视频，特别是那些以<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.vulture.com/article/jayquan-mckenley-chii-wvtzz-eric-adams-drill.html#_ga=2.8250674.1462920847.1690910851-270587328.1687895713">练习音乐</a>为特色的视频，该视频于 2010 年代初在芝加哥开始，以明确地引诱“opps”或竞争对手为主导。这些视频与多起枪击事件有关。不过，冲突通常是由更平凡的在线活动引发的。青少年在 Instagram 帖子中引诱竞争对手，或者在私人聊天中受到盟友的刺激。在 Instagram 和 Facebook 上，他们直播入侵敌方领土的情况，并面临“放下大头针”的挑战——暴露自己的位置，否则就会被视为胆小鬼。他们在 Snapchat 照片或 YouTube 和 TikTok 视频中挥舞枪支，这可能会激起对手的回应，并迫使持枪者实际使用它。<br><br> “如果你不监控社交媒体，你就会想知道为什么 1000 人突然在市中心打架。”<br><br> 12 月，我在宾夕法尼亚州胡茨代尔的州立监狱见到了 21 岁的布兰登·奥利维耶里 (Brandon Olivieri)，他因谋杀罪正在监狱服刑。奥利维耶里说，2017 年，他试图在费城南部的其他青少年的地盘上出售大麻，结果与他们发生了冲突。后来，在奥利维耶里和他的朋友们的 Instagram 私人聊天中，有人发布了一张银色 0.45 口径手枪的照片。然后另一名成员尼古拉斯·托雷利(Nicholas Torelli)在人行道上贴出了一张猫粪便的照片，并配上标题“布兰登在对方领地拉了屎。”这是一个玩笑，但谈话很快就变得咄咄逼人。那天晚些时候，奥利维耶里要求托雷利将对手的照片放到聊天中，这样每个人都可以看到他们的样子。托雷利照做了，根据法庭记录，奥利维耶里回答说他会“把他们全部杀掉”。<br><br>当月晚些时候，奥利维耶里、托雷利和两个朋友遇到了他们的四个对手，双方发生了激烈的争吵、打斗以及银手枪中的三声枪响。奥利维耶里小组的成员卡利尔·米勒 (Caleer Miller) 被一颗子弹击中。另一名船员中的萨尔瓦托·迪努比勒 (Salvatore DiNubile) 也被击中。两人都死了；他们当时 16 岁。奥利维耶里因迪努比勒之死而被判一级谋杀罪，因米勒之死而被判三级谋杀罪。 （托雷利作证指控奥利维耶里，但没有受到指控。）奥利维耶里被判处 37 年至无期徒刑。<br><br> DiNubile 的父亲也叫 Salvatore，他认为在线分享威胁的能力鼓励了奥利维耶里和他的朋友们制造威胁；完成这些任务后，他们感到有必要坚持到底。 “你说过你要对付这个家伙。这是你的机会，”他告诉我。 “你试图辜负他自创的黑帮心态。”奥利维耶里坚称自己是清白的，并表示自己不是开枪的人，但他也同意，他和他的朋友经常在网上吹牛来互相炒作。 “这就是我们所说的造假，”他解释道。<br><br><span class="smallcaps">去年，</span>随着华盛顿特区的青少年枪击受害者人数攀升至三位数，该市负责培训社区成员预防暴力的和平学院举办了一场专门针对社交媒体的 Zoom 会议。华盛顿特区总检察长办公室的阿明·比尔 (Ameen Beale) 分享了他的屏幕，展示了典型的网络冲突最终导致死亡的场景。<br><br>演示以一张 2019 年发布在 Instagram 上的照片开始，照片中当地说唱歌手 AhkDaClicka 在地铁上；标题嘲笑他在没有枪的情况下被对手抓住。随后出现了 AhkDaClicka 和竞争对手说唱歌手 Walkdown Will 之间的私人消息截图，后者在 Instagram Live 上嘲讽地发布了该消息。接下来，AhkDaClicka 的 Instagram 故事侮辱了另一名据称参加地铁冲突的说唱歌手，以及 AhkDaClicka<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=PFxpUO0J9E4">讲述这一事件</a>的 YouTube 视频，其中包括“给我一把格洛克，给我指点一下对手”这句台词。不久之后，即 2020 年 1 月，AhkDaClicka 被枪杀。他18岁；他的真名是马利克·西塞。那年 5 月，警方逮捕了同为 18 岁的 Walkdown Will—William Whitaker。去年 10 月，他承认犯有二级谋杀罪。<br><br>比尔的演讲让一些与会者目瞪口呆。 “我不敢相信这种不成熟和愚蠢的程度已经成为常态，”一位网友在聊天中写道。另一位提出了会议期间迫在眉睫的问题：该市预防暴力领域是否有人要求社交媒体公司限制煽动性内容？<br><br> “我认为我们没有取得太大进展，”比尔承认。他说，当市政府寻求删除帖子时，这些公司以有关言论自由的模糊论点拒绝了其请求。即使社交媒体平台确实删除了某个帖子，也可能已经有 20 个人与数百或数千人分享了该帖子。考虑到在线生活的节奏，您可能会花五年时间尝试阻止一个平台上的有害内容，结果所有活动都迁移到另一个平台。<br><br> <a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/technology/archive/2023/06/social-media-teen-mental-health-crisis-research-limitations/674371/">阅读：没有人确切知道社交媒体对青少年做了什么</a><br><br>我向拥有 YouTube 的谷歌发言人询问了关于 AhkDaClicka 视频（其中包含有关 Glock 的台词）以及去年夏天发布的另一则视频（标题为“Pull Da Plug”）的情况。照片中，肯塔基州路易斯维尔的一名说唱歌手和其他大约十几名年轻人显然正在庆祝一场枪击事件，这场枪击事件导致一名男子依靠生命维持系统（后来他去世了）。路易斯维尔暴力预防机构的负责人告诉我，受害者的家人要求谷歌删除该视频，但该视频并未删除，观看次数超过 15,000 次。发言人杰克·马龙告诉我，该公司通常有一个“相当高的门槛”来确定音乐视频煽动暴力，部分原因是公司政策<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://support.google.com/youtube/answer/2802268#zippy=%2Cother-types-of-content-that-violate-this-policy">允许艺术内容例外</a>。<br><br>我与 Malon 以及他在 Snap 和 Meta（拥有 Facebook 和 Instagram）的同行的谈话给我留下的印象是，与更引人注目的辩论相比，社交媒体平台相对较少考虑它们在助长常规枪支暴力方面的作用。审查煽动性政治言论。 Meta 向我指出了它的“ <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://transparency.fb.com/en-gb/policies/community-standards">社区标准</a>”，其中充满了灰色地带的声明，例如“我们还尝试考虑语言和上下文，以便将随意的声明与对公共或个人安全构成可信威胁的内容区分开来。” Snap 辩称，它的平台比其他平台更加良性，因为帖子的设计目的是消失，并且主要由朋友查看。我也联系了 TikTok，但该公司没有回应。<br><br>与此同时，社区只能自力更生。但预防暴力团体主要由成长于智能手机时代之前的中年男性主导。他们更愿意亲自干预，而不是解读 TikTok 上的威胁。在大流行之前，匹兹堡主要反暴力组织的一名实习生扫描了被认为有卷入冲突风险的年轻人在社交媒体上发布的帖子。市政府与暴力预防组织的联络人康奈尔·琼斯牧师告诉我，实习生曾经发现青少年之间正在网上酝酿一场争斗，其中一些人获得了枪支。琼斯带了参与者和他们的母亲来，化解了局势。然后，实习生离开小镇去法学院学习，该组织又恢复了对此类团体来说更典型的临时方法。 “如果你不监控社交媒体，你就会想知道为什么 1,000 人突然在市中心打架，”琼斯悲伤地说道。 7月初，巴尔的摩一个街区派对上发生的枪击事件证实了他的担忧：尽管该事件在社交媒体上被广泛讨论，但现场并没有警察；后来，一段视频流传，一名青少年在聚会上炫耀一把疑似枪支的东西。枪击事件造成两人死亡、28 人受伤。<br><br>十年前，宾夕法尼亚大学社会政策、传播学和精神病学教授德斯蒙德·厄普顿·巴顿 (Desmond Upton Patton) 获得了第一笔拨款，用于研究他所谓的“ <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/abs/pii/S0747563212003779">互联网攻击</a>”。他的研究团队与哥伦比亚大学的一个团队共同设计了算法，用于分析 Twitter 上的语言、图像甚至表情符号，并识别有伤害自己或他人风险的用户。这些算法在识别不断升级的在线纠纷方面显示出了希望。但他从未允许使用它们，担心它们与警方的监视工作相似，后者只能进行侧写而不是预防。 “也许有一个更聪明的人能够弄清楚如何合乎道德地做到这一点，”他对我说。<br><br>目前，该系统无法预测暴力行为，甚至经常无法对社交媒体上指控其有罪的人定罪。五月，三名青少年因谋杀贾雷尔·杰克逊和沙贾汉·麦卡斯基尔而在费城受审。枪击发生时，两人 17 岁，第三人 16 岁。社交媒体活动构成了检察官证据的关键部分：Instagram 帖子和视频显示，三名被告驾驶着一辆与那辆看似一模一样的黑色 SUV那辆车停在杰克逊的车旁边。其他帖子显示，其中两人持有一把与枪击事件中使用的描述相符的枪。经过一天的审议，陪审团宣判他们无谋杀罪，并裁定其中两名被告仅犯有武器罪。这一判决让受害者家属感到震惊。 “对于我和我的家人来说，[审判]就像一场为期 7 天的葬礼，”贾雷尔的母亲莫妮克·杰克逊告诉我。后来，调查谋杀案的侦探向她推测，此类案件的陪审员往往很难掌握社交媒体的基本机制以及它对年轻人互动的重要性。正如巴顿对我所说的那样，“我们一次又一次地低估了社交媒体与现实生活的区别。这<i>就是</i>生活。”<br><br> <em><small>This article has been updated to clarify YouTube&#39;s policy for determining which videos are removed for inciting violence.</small></em><br><br> <small><em>This article is a collaboration between</em> The Atlantic <em>and ProPublica. It appears in the <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/magazine/toc/2023/09">September 2023</a> print edition with the headline “Killer Apps.”</em></small><br><br></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Tue, 08 Aug 2023 11:00:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.theatlantic.com/magazine/archive/2023/09/jarell-jackson-shahjahan-mccaskill-killed-philadelphia-social-media/674760/</guid><link/> https://www.theatlantic.com/magazine/archive/2023/09/jarell-jackson-shahjahan-mccaskill-killed-philadelphia-social-media/674760/ </item><item><title><![CDATA[Trump Is Acting Like He’s Cornered]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div> The former president&#39;s response to the latest indictment suggests a man rattled in a way he seldom has been before. <br><figure><img src="https://cdn.theatlantic.com/thumbor/rn9qeKhbA3Ed8QcVbC6TwdHXfyQ=/0x0:4800x2700/960x540/media/img/mt/2023/08/trump-1/original.jpg" alt="唐纳德·特朗普，从后面看" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><figcaption> Christopher Aluka Berry / Reuters</figcaption></figure> In some ways, Donald Trump&#39;s mental state is more transparent than nearly any public figure&#39;s: He has no shame, little discretion, and ample channels to broadcast his feelings in real time. Yet his constant stream of consciousness and always elevated dudgeon make it hard to parse the finer fluctuations in his mood.<br><br> Even so, the former president&#39;s public behavior since Special Counsel Jack Smith <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2023/08/trump-indicted-january-6-jack-smith/674886/">indicted him last week</a> suggests a man feeling cornered. This isn&#39;t to say that Trump <em>is</em> cornered—his ability to escape tough situations makes him the envy of <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.newsweek.com/cats-nine-lives-myth-explained-1643381">every house cat</a> —but his handling of the case suggests a man rattled in a way he seldom has been before.<br><br> The former president has attacked Smith in terms that are strikingly personal, even for him. He has also attacked Tanya Chutkan, the federal judge assigned to hear the case. He delivered angry speeches in Alabama and South Carolina. He jeered the US Women&#39;s National Team, blamed President Joe Biden for its early exit from the World Cup, and <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://truthsocial.com/@realDonaldTrump/posts/110842705795010789">unintelligibly ridiculed</a> former House Speaker Nancy Pelosi (“She is a Wicked Witch whose husbands journey from hell starts and finishes with her. She is a sick &amp; demented psycho who will someday live in HELL!”). He sent his attorney out to do all five major Sunday-morning TV programs. <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.thedailybeast.com/theres-a-good-reason-trump-aides-dont-think-the-new-indictment-is-a-joke?ref=home?ref=home?ref=home"><em>The Daily Beast</em> spoke</a> with Trump insiders who reported serious apprehensions inside his camp.<br><br> <a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2023/08/trump-indicted-january-6-jack-smith/674886/">David A. Graham: Trump attempted a brazen, dead-serious attack on American democracy</a><br><br> But what neither he nor his allies have done is offer a coherent account of his actions—one that would suggest that he didn&#39;t conspire to overthrow the duly elected government. This is likely for the simple reason that he conspired to overthrow the duly elected government.<br><br> “Deranged Jack Smith is going before his number one draft pick, the Judge of his &#39;dreams&#39; (WHO MUST BE RECUSED!), in an attempt to take away my FIRST AMENDMENT RIGHTS - This, despite the fact that he, the DOJ, and his many Thug prosecutors, are illegally leaking, everything and anything, to the Fake News Media!!!” <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://truthsocial.com/@realDonaldTrump/posts/110848362917019858">Trump wrote</a> on his Truth Social site this morning.<br><br> This message followed a string of other rants in recent days, including attacks on former Vice President Mike Pence (“Liddle&#39; Mike Pence, a man who was about to be ousted as Governor Indiana until I came along and made him VP, has gone to the Dark Side”) and Chutkan (“THERE IS NO WAY I CAN GET A FAIR TRIAL WITH THE JUDGE “ASSIGNED” TO THE RIDICULOUS FREEDOM OF SPEECH/FAIR ELECTIONS CASE”).<br><br> Attacking the judge and the prosecutor in your case is not generally recommended as a defense strategy, but then, Trump has little use for courtesy, niceties, or basic common sense. Smith is clearly paying attention; prosecutors cited an ambiguously threatening social-media post in a court filing just hours after it was posted. (“IF YOU GO AFTER ME, I&#39;M COMING AFTER YOU!&quot; the message said; a Trump spokesperson claimed that this was actually directed at “the RINO, China-loving, dishonest special interest groups and Super PACs.”) The difference between Trump&#39;s broadsides against Chutkan, a Black Obama appointee who hasn&#39;t even had a chance to make any consequential decisions in the case yet, and his lack of criticism for Judge Aileen Cannon, the Trump appointee overseeing the Florida case over his mishandling of classified documents, is notable if not surprising.<br><br> <a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2023/08/donald-trump-indictment-gop-jan-6/674895/">Ronald Brownstein: Trump&#39;s threat to democracy is now systemic</a><br><br> Discerning Trump&#39;s agitation is easy enough; determining the goal of his outbursts is not so straightforward. One interpretation is that he&#39;s trying to goad Smith&#39;s team and turn its members from prosecutors into persecutors, baiting them to overreact or demand onerous conditions, which Trump could in turn use to demand a venue change or appeal a conviction. But this is reminiscent of the <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://knowyourmeme.com/memes/profit"><em>South Park</em> –birthed underpants-gnome meme</a> : The first steps and desired outcome are clear, but it&#39;s completely mysterious what the middle steps might be. For all Trump&#39;s comments that Smith is “deranged,” the special counsel instead seems preternaturally, even uncannily, impassive. Chutkan, like other DC judges, has rejected prior claims that January 6 trials can&#39;t be fairly held in the district.<br><br> An alternative theory is that Trump is just playing to the court of public opinion rather than the court of law. Yesterday, Trump&#39;s attorney John Lauro did the circuit of Sunday shows, a maneuver that Beltway nerds call the “Full Ginsburg,” after William Ginsburg, an attorney for Monica Lewinsky who pioneered it to respond to reports about his client&#39;s relationship with then-President Bill Clinton. It&#39;s a powerful public-relations tool— <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Full_Ginsburg">used by candidates for president</a> , for example—but somewhat baffling as a pretrial maneuver.<br><br> Trump is often more interested in rousing his supporters than pursuing a prudent defense, apparently concluding that whatever his problems with the law, his political clout will be enough to evade or at least finesse the jeopardy. In the two federal cases against him, he may finally be facing charges that are not so easily circumvented, but his response has not necessarily caught up.<br><br> <a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2023/08/jeffrey-clark-doj-weaponization-trump-indictment/674898/">David A. Graham: The real weaponization of the Justice Department</a><br><br> On some level, the PR offensive might be working. More than half of Americans, according to a new <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.cbsnews.com/news/trump-indictment-jan-6-opinion-poll-2023-08-06/">CBS News/YouGov poll</a> , think the charges against Trump are aimed at hurting his 2024 campaign, though solid majorities also think the charges are about upholding rule of law and defending democracy. But the actual arguments Lauro offered on TV don&#39;t seem especially well crafted, and seem likely instead to reinforce the reality that whether the public wants him convicted or not, it is appalled by Trump&#39;s attempt at stealing the election.<br><br> Lauro argued in different appearances that Trump&#39;s alleged behavior was “aspirational.” For example, “What President Trump didn&#39;t do is direct Vice President Pence to do anything,” Lauro said on CNN. “He asked him in an aspirational way.” He also called Trump&#39;s request for Georgia Secretary of State Brad Raffensperger to “find 11,780 votes” an “aspirational ask.” This is the kind of distinction without a difference that gives legalism a bad name. Lauro also said that even if Trump committed a “technical violation of the Constitution,” he didn&#39;t commit a crime. But telling the public that your client violated the Constitution seems like a questionable PR decision.<br><br> Neither Lauro, in his five appearances, nor Trump, going back to his initial response to the indictment, has actually rebutted the charges. Trump has claimed that the government is attacking his right to free speech, but he has made nearly no effort to question the specifics of the charges. A rare example is his denial of Pence&#39;s claim that Trump said he was “too honest.” More broadly, Trump hasn&#39;t offered any bigger explanation for his weeks-long push to subvert the election. If Trump is acting as though he&#39;s cornered, that is because he doesn&#39;t have a good answer to this question.<br><br></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Mon, 07 Aug 2023 19:37:08 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2023/08/donald-trumps-unhinged-attacks-smith-and-chutkan/674945/</guid><link/> https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2023/08/donald-trumps-unhinged-attacks-smith-and-chutkan/674945/</item></channel></rss>